<FIRST>r a AM-TankerSpill-Wildlife     07-08 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill-Wildlife,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bird Deaths from Tanker Spill Continue to Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil contamination from the Exxon Valdez
spill has killed about 27,000 sea birds and the death toll can be
expected to increase for at least a few more months, the U.S. Fish &amp;
Wildlife Service said.
   ``We just don't know how long it's going to go on,'' said Vivian
Mendenhall, marine bird coordinator at the agency's Anchorage office.
   She said the numbers of dead birds being found has dropped off
since the initial fatalities after the tanker struck a reef in
Prince William Sound on March 24, spilling nearly 11 million gallons
of crude oil spilled into the sea.
   In general, seabirds over water cannot detect oil and do not
discriminate between clean places and dirty places in deciding where
to touch down, Mendenhall said.
   Figures released Friday by a federal information office in Valdez
show 563 of 1,326 seabirds received alive at rescue centers have
been released. Nearly 600 have died at the facilities.
   Fish &amp; Wildlife Service spokesman Bruce Batten said 103 bald
eagles are known to have died from the spill. Alaska's bald eagle
population is about 35,000, with 3,000 of the birds in Prince
William Sound and 5,000 in other areas contaminated with oil, he
said.
   The federal tally sheet released Friday also reported 843 otters
dead. About two-thirds of the 343 received alive by rescue centers
have survived. Batten said a Fish &amp; Wildlife Service plan for the
release of treated otters likely will be issued next week.
</TEXT>
