<FIRST>r e BC-Ballet     07-08 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ballet,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kirov Ballet Dances Poetic `Giselle'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ballet goers who weren't pleased that the Kirov
Ballet opened its U.S. tour here Monday with the unfamiliar ``Le
Corsaire'' could rejoice Friday night when the well-known
``Giselle'' was danced like a beautiful poem.
   Farukh Ruzimatov, thus far the most impressive dancer in this
high-caliber company, danced Count Albrecht. It is thrilling to see
an artist so secure in his technique that he never has to press but
lets his art flow, with time to present subtleties.
   Ruzimatov looked noble in features and bearing but so did Gennadi
Babanin as the woodsman Hilarion, so it was plausible that Giselle
would accept the count as rural and fall in love with him. Ruzimatov
made Count Albrecht really in love with Giselle. His partnering of
her was gentle and attentive. When his royal fiancee arrives, he
walks with her with ill grace instead of immediately ditching
Giselle for her, as some do when dancing the count.
   And Ruzimatov made some sudden, very exciting bursts into
dramatic dancing.
   Zhanna Ayupova danced Giselle. She was good but not riveting
early in Act 1. But she made her mad scene unusually poignant and
she was exquisite in Act 2, as the ghost of herself. The
Giselle-Albrecht duets were tenderly emotional. All the principal
dancers conveyed the emotions of the characters they danced.
   The corps de ballet dancing was shimmering, accurate but soft,
without the sharp edge that the word accurate can convey. This
production isn't afraid to have the orchestra playing in Act 2 with
nobody on stage, which strongly builds anticipation.
   There are moments from this exceptional ``Giselle'' to cherish
and remember.
   After the Kirov Ballet closes at the Metropolitan Opera July 22,
it will appear at Kennedy Center in Washington July 25 to Aug. 6,
the War Memorial Opera House in San Francisco Aug. 9 to 16 and
Orange County Performing Arts Center, Costa Mesa, Calif., Aug. 18 to
27.
</TEXT>
