<FIRST>r a AM-LutheranConvention     07-08 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lutheran Convention,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Lutheran Church-Missouri Synod Triennial Convention Begins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Lutheran Church-Missouri Synod triennial
convention began Friday in Wichita with a prayer and communion
service.
   About 1,100 voting delegates, half of them clergy and half lay
members, were expected at the 57th Regular Convention of the 2.6
million member St. Louis-based denomination.
   The election of church officers is scheduled Saturday. The
current president, the Rev. Ralph A. Bohlmann, 57, has led the
denomination since 1981 when he was part of a conservative movement
in the synod.
   Some conservatives in the church now contend Bohlmann has become
too moderate. They led an effort to unseat him at the 1986
convention, but narrowly failed.
   Other candidates for president during Saturday's elections
include the Rev. Eugene W. Bunkowske, 53, chairman of the Department
of Missions at Concordia Theological Seimary, Ft. Wayne, Ind.; the
Rev. Robert D. Preus, 64, president of Concordia Theological
Seminary, Fort Wayne, Ind.; the Rev. Robert C. Sauer, 67, St.
Charles Mo., a veteran pastor who is chairman of the synod's
Catechism Translation Task Force; and the Rev. George F, Wollenburg,
58, parish pastor of Christ The King in Billings, Mont. and second
vice president of the synod.
   During the course of the convention, delegates will consider 132
resolutions including two on social issues previously unaddressed by
the synod.
   A resolution on homelessness would encourage the synod's housing
task force to assist congregations with housing ministries and
monitor federal legislation affecting the homeless.
   A resolution on AIDS recalls Jesus' example of ``unconditional
love, care and compassion in the treatment of the afflicted'' and
urges congregations to commit themselves to minister to victims of
the disease.
   Other resolutions address evangelism, a possible synod name
change to reflect its international scope, a task force on black
ministry, urban ministry planning and outreach to Jewish people.
   The convention is scheduled to run through July 14.
</TEXT>
