<FIRST>r a PM-SewerFest     07-08 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SewerFest,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction-Weary Residents Grab Plungers for SewerFest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OBERLIN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents weary of wending their way through
sewer construction will grab plungers and kazoos for some
lighthearted fun at a SewerFest later this month.
   ``It started out as one of those hokey things,'' said Jan Pierce,
a coordinator of the event. ``I haven't laughed so much in ages
putting it together. We hope the community will have some fun with
it.''
   Since last year, barricaded streets have forced Oberlin motorists
to take inconvenient routes and the rough roads have rattled car
alignments. Construction is set for fall completion.
   Ms. Pierce said she had to buy three new tires because of the
rough going on streets along construction sites.
   ``We don't know from day to day how the streets will go,'' said
Ms. Pierce. ``It's frustrating. We all feel it on a personal level.''
   The two-day SewerFest, sponsored by the Oberlin Downtown
Merchants Association, features a parade July 21 with jackhammers, a
dump truck and the city sewer-cleaning machine, and a kazoo marching
band with people dressed in sewer-cleaning uniforms.
   Residents are invited to submit essays on their worst ``war
story'' because of the construction , with a $250 prize for the
winning entry. The essays will be bound and given to the library's
community history department.
   Oberlin Police Chief Robert Jones said officers who often got the
complaints for the blocked and torn-up streets can laugh it off
during the festival.
   ``Policemen are always at the brunt of all the complaints,''
Jones said. ``You get used to it and just smile. The humorous idea
of (SewerFest) was quite refreshing.''
   The festival, he said, will be a way to ``let out the
frustrations people have been going through.''
</TEXT>
