<FIRST>r a PM-SharkFisherman     07-08 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shark Fisherman,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legendary Shark Fisherman Must Take Exam To Get Captain's License
Back</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTAUK, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charter boat captain Frank Mundus, said to
be the inspiration for the shark fisherman in the movie ``Jaws,''
has for years wrestled fearlessly with the mightiest of the seas.
   But now the 63-year-old folk hero has a new challenge. After 45
years on the water, he forgot to renew his charter boat captain's
license and must pass a tough Coast Guard exam to get it back.
   ``It's bloody embarrassing,'' said Mundus, as he stood in front
of his boat, Cricket II, after an all-day outing Thursday.
   ``I'm scared to take that test,'' said Mundus, who has only a
ninth-grade education. ``It's all book work. But I'll just have to
knuckle down and study. The rules are the rules.''
   ``He doesn't have to study. He knows everything,'' said Coast
Guard spokesman James McGranachan, who added that the service told
Mundus they would help him by reading the questions to him.
   ``A lot of people fail the test but not people like him,''
McGranachan said. ``It's in his blood by now. ... Everything we have
heard about him is that he is a good captain.''
   Mundus said he forgot to renew his license when it expired in May
1988 and during the following one-year grace period because he was
working hard and was distracted by his upcoming wedding to a
28-year-old English woman.
   The legendary Mundus, who was wearing a gold pierced earring in
his left ear and a pearly white shark's tooth around his neck, still
takes groups out on his boat but must have a licensed charter
captain aboard with him.
   ``It's only a minor inconvenience,'' said the balding, lanky man.
   But he was quick to add, ``I'm still the boss here. I wouldn't
trust my captain's chair to anybody.''
   ``If it weren't for the people I take out, I wouldn't stay
alive,'' he said. ``I have more fun going out than they do.''
   Mundus, a native of Point Pleasant, N.J., has been a charter boat
captain in Montauk since 1951.
   Stories of Mundus' shark fishing adventures are said to have
inspired Peter Benchley to write the best-selling novel, ``Jaws.''
Benchley, according to Mundus, went on a few shark hunts with him in
the 1970s. The shark fisherman character was called Quint in the
movie.
   Mundus says his personality goes from carefree to serious when he
sees a shark he wants.
   ``If I see something over 1,000 pounds, I say to myself, `I'm
going to get that fish.' I don't care if we tear the boat apart to
get it.''
   In 1964, Mundus' boat harpooned a 4,500-pound white shark which
is listed in the Guinness Book of World Records as the largest shark
harpooned in this century. In 1986, his boat took in a 3,500-pound
shark which he said is the largest fish in the world to be caught by
a rod and reel.
   The head of that shark hangs in Mundus' house and it is one of
its teeth that hangs around Mundus' neck.
   But his years on the water are winding down.
   His 42-foot custom-built fishing boat is up for sale at $150,000
and he said if he sells it next summer it will probably be his last
season running the charter.
   He plans to retire to Hawaii with his wife, Jenny. The couple met
after she wrote him from her home in Cornwall, England, of her
interest in sharks. They corresponded for several months before
Mundus invited her to the United States last November.
   Mundus said he is building his Hawaiian retirement home ``in the
hills amidst the fruit trees.''
   But he knows he will always think about his days on the water.
``When it's time to go, I'll just give a sigh of relief and walk
away thinking we caught all the largest fish.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
