<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Fed-InterestRates Bjt   07-08 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fed-Interest Rates, Bjt,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts See Fed Actions Dropping Prime Rate Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an move that many economists expect will
make borrowing easier, the Federal Reserve eased credit conditions
for the second time in four weeks.
   Analysts predicted the development would send a variety of
consumer and business interest rates lower in coming weeks,
including home mortgage rates and commercial banks' prime-lending
rate.
   One analyst said a one-half percentage point reduction in the
prime rate, the benchmark rate for many consumer loans, could come
as early as Monday. The prime rate stands at 11 percent.
   ``The Fed is easing and there is clear evidence that we have
passed the peak on interest rates,'' said David Wyss, an economist
with DRI-McGraw Hill, an economic consulting company in Lexington,
Mass.
   The Fed began easing its credit policy last month, changing
course after a yearlong effort to drive rates higher as a way of
dampening inflationary pressures.
   That credit squeeze had brought complaints from President Bush
and others that the central bank ran the risk of pushing the country
into a recession.
   The central bank is trying to engineer a so-called
``soft-landing'' for the economy in which growth slows enough to
dampen inflationary pressures but without a recession.
   Economists based their belief that the Fed eased again this week
on a slight decline in the federal funds rate, which edged down 0.25
percentage point to 9.25 percent Thursday and Friday.
   The federal funds rate is the interest that banks charge each
other to make overnight loans. It is influenced by daily decisions
the central bank makes on how much money to make available to the
banking system and is considered the best early warning signal of
Fed intentions to loosen or tighten credit conditions.
   The funds' rate dropped for the first time in a year in early
June, when it declined from 9.75 percent to 9.5 percent.
   Many analysts said they expected to see further 0.25 percentage
point declines over the next several months if inflation moderates
further and various business barometers continue signaling a
slowdown.
   The Labor Department reported Friday the nation's unemployment
rate climbed from 5.2 percent to 5.3 percent in June, reflecting
continuing job losses in manufacturing and construction.
   David Jones, an economist with Aubrey G. Lanston &amp; Co., a
government securities dealer, said he expected the Fed's
credit-loosening moves would prompt banks to cut their prime-lending
rate to 10.5 percent, perhaps as early as Monday.
   Other economists predicted that mortgage rates would soon dip
back into the single-digit range, perhaps falling to as low as 9.5
percent for fixed-rate mortgages. Such mortgages stand at 10.03
percent, down from 10.07 percent the previous week, according to a
national survey released Friday by the Federal Home Loan Mortgage
Corp.
   The latest easing came while Fed policy-makers were holding two
days of meetings as part of their midyear review of monetary
strategy.
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan will reveal details of
this week's discussions when he delivers the Fed's midyear
assessment of the economy in congressional testimony July 20.
   At a May 16 meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee, Fed
policy-makers decided to leave credit conditions unchanged. However,
they noted a variety of economic statistics pointing to slower
growth, according to minutes of that meeting released Friday.
   The FOMC is composed of members of the Federal Reserve Board in
Washington and five of the 12 Fed regional bank presidents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
