<DOCNO> AP890708-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0617EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HUDProbe Bjt   07-08 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Probe, Bjt,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Says Pierce Failed As HUD Manager</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing Secretary Jack Kemp says more agency
programs may be suspended, but promises to revive the
scandal-wracked department and ``make sure the money gets to hands
of needy people, not greedy people.''
   Kemp also said Friday that his predecessor, Samuel Pierce, shares
blame for HUD's problems, which congressional and agency
investigators believe have cost the government hundreds of millions,
if not billions, of dollars.
   Kemp promised a thorough review of the Department of Housing and
Urban Development and made his most direct comments to date on his
assessment of Pierce.
   ``I'm making a lot of changes, so that, by definition, is
suggesting that Secretary Pierce unfortunately _ a very decent and
honest man _ did not in my view manage HUD as carefully or closely
as it should have been managed,'' Kemp told reporters after speaking
to a Republican group.
   ``That reflects on Mr. Pierce and, I say this with sadness not
anger, it reflects on the Reagan administration.''
   Kemp said said he and President Bush will be to blame if they are
unsuccessful in reforming the agency, a massive task that involves
major internal reviews of virtually all the agency's major programs.
   Three programs have been suspended or canceled, and Kemp said
``there may be more'' as his review progresses.
   ``But I'm not going to announce them today,'' he said.
   Kemp, in promising to revive the agency, dismissed questions from
the congressman heading a subcommittee investigation of HUD's
problems. Kemp is to testify next week before the subcommittee.
   Rep. Thomas Lantos, D-Calif., head of the House Government
Operations subcommittee on employment and housing, said Thursday
that he feared Kemp was using the investigation to kill housing
programs.
   ``I don't want to end the system _ I want to make it work,'' Kemp
said. ``We're going to spend a lot of money but I want to make sure
the money gets to the hands of needy people, not greedy people.''
   Pierce has been recalled to testify before the subcommittee to
face questions about a North Carolina project HUD funded that was
pushed by a one-time law partner of the former HUD secretary.
   A HUD official who approved the funding, Janet Hale, now works at
the Office of Management and Budget and was told late Thursday that
she should steer clear of HUD matters that could be related to the
investigations.
   Ms. Hale's predecessor as deputy secretary of housing, Shirley
McVay Wiseman, has said she quit because Pierce wanted her to
approve the North Carolina project over the objections of career HUD
officials. Pierce promoted Ms. Hale to succeed Wiseman and she
approved the project in 1985.
   Ms. Hale also faces questioning over her response to an audit by
HUD's inspector general that found numerous abuses of a program
under which HUD jointly guaranteed loans for developers with lenders
that HUD now says has cost the agency more than $100 million.
   HUD Inspector General Paul Adams told Congress last week that a
1984 audit found that lenders on eight projects under the program
had inflated appraisals by $36 million and that auditors then
proposed a series of corrective measures to agency officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
