<FIRST>r w PM-Hispanics     07-08 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hispanics,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democratic Leader, Labor Secretary Address Hispanic Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats and Republicans are wooing the
nation's oldest and largest Hispanic group.
   Democratic National Chairman Ronald H. Brown and Labor Secretary
Elizabeth Dole appeared within hours of each other Friday at the
annual convention of the National League of United Latin American
Citizens _ Brown offering more political clout and Dole more jobs.
   The remarks reflected the value the two parties have placed on
Hispanic voters in recent elections, highlighted last year by
promises from both presidential nominees that they would name a
Hispanic to a Cabinet post.
   Brown told the group that Republicans were merely paying lip
service to Hispanics.
   ``The difference is very stark and distinct,'' said Brown.
``Republicans take a Madison Avenue, media approach. That's the way
you deal with the American public. With little slogans, with little,
oversimplified phrases but with no understanding of what the
problems of people are and how you deal with the problems of people.
Selling candidates ... It's like selling toothpaste or detergent.''
   By contrast, said Brown, ``The Democratic Party is committed to
the economic and political empowerment of the Hispanic Community. I
don't think its just coincidence that every member of the
Congressional Hispanic Caucus is a Democrat.''
   Dole, speaking later in the day, emphasized a pending jobs bill
rather than politics.
   Mrs. Dole said her top priority is to reduce minority youth
unemployment and she asked the group's support for a Bush
administration bill that would reform the federal job-training
program.
   The legislation, she said, would add skills training, literacy,
remedial education and counseling provisions to the Job Training
Partnership Act. She urged members of the group to attend a Senate
subcommittee session next week at which the bill will be drafted.
   She also pledged more jobs at her department for Hispanics. She
said Hispanic employment at the Transportation Department rose by 25
percent while she was secretary during the Reagan administration,
and said, ``I intend to get the same results at the Department of
Labor.''
   Brown said that for Democrats ``there is nothing more crucial
than the 1990 census'' in its efforts to reach minorities. He said
the party will be working to make sure Hispanics and blacks who
might not be counted do end up on the Census Bureau rolls.
   The 1990 census will be used in redrawing congressional district
boundaries.
   The Census Bureau estimated the Hispanic population at 17{
million in 1985.
</TEXT>
