<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge put Jake ``The Snake'' Roberts
in the slammer pending sentencing after his conviction for punching
a drinking partner.
   Circuit Judge Gayle Graziano ordered Roberts _ whose real name is
Aurelian Smith Jr. _ locked up after he was convicted Wednesday of
aggravated battery. The action revoked Roberts' $2,500 bail and
forced him to await sentencing in the Volusia County Jail.
   The 34-year-old Roberts _ who got his stage name from the 8-foot
boa constrictor he carries in the ring _ was arrested May 8 in
Orlando.
   A jury convicted the 6-foot-5-inch, 249-pound wrestler of
punching 5-foot-7-inch, 160-pound John Bartlett in the face and
abdomen after a night of drinking in December.
   Bartlett, 27, told police he met Roberts at a bar. While later
riding in a car, Roberts made disparaging remarks about Daytona
Beach and its women, Bartlett said.
   When Bartlett defended Daytona Beach, the wrestler stopped the
car and slugged him, Bartlett told police.
   Roberts testified that Bartlett started the fight and that
Roberts just defended himself.
   Bartlett, who said he needed surgery to repair the bone around
his eye, said he was pleased with the verdict.
   Aggravated battery carries a maximum sentence of 15 years in
prison, but sentencing guidelines call for 12 to 30 months for
those, like Roberts, with no record.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Akihito has paid taxes on his share of the
$13.4 million estate of his late father, Hirohito, the government
announced.
   The Imperial Household Agency, which manages palace affairs, said
Friday that the possessions of Emperor Hirohito, who died of cancer
Jan. 7, were divided equally between his son and his mother, Empress
Dowager Nagako.
   The government statement did not disclose the amount of tax
Akihito paid. Nagako was entitled to a tax exemption as the spouse
of the deceased and did not pay any tax, it said.
   Excluded from the tax assessment were the three sacred treasures
_ a sword, mirror and curved jewel _ which symbolize the imperial
institution. Also exempted: more than 3,000 art objects collected by
the imperial family, which will be donated to the country, and a
$360,000 contribution to the Japan Red Cross.
   It was the first time the imperial family has revealed the value
of its possessions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dalai Lama, who was chased from
his Tibetan homeland 30 years ago by Chinese troops, said the recent
massacre of students in Beijing mirrored the repression Tibet has
suffered.
   `Of course, it is a very sad event, a kind of self-destruction,''
the Dalai Lama said Friday of the army assault on Tiananmen Square
last month.``We have experienced the same since last March in Tibet.
It has been a tragedy.''
   Tibet has been under martial law since March 5, when bloody
protests marked the 30th anniversary of an unsuccessful three-week
uprising against Chinese rule. The Dalai Lama was forced to flee the
country March 31, 1959.
   Despite the crackdown, the Dalai Lama said Chinese students would
win their struggle for democracy as long as they refrain from
violence. ``I always have believed in human determination and the
human spirit to overcome,'' he said at a news conference.
   The religious leader revered by most Tibetans as a living Buddha
is on a 17-day visit to Los Angeles to address followers of the
2,500-year-old faith.
