<FIRST>u i BC-China-Expulsion     07-08 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-Expulsion,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>China Expels Another American Reporter, 4th Since Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese authorities ordered the expulsion of
another American reporter Saturday, charging him with violating his
visa status and the terms of martial law.
   Mark Hopkins, correspondent for the U.S. government-run Voice of
America radio network, was given 72 hours to leave the country, said
VOA Director Richard W. Carlson in a telephone interview from
Washington.
   Hopkins was called in Saturday morning to the Beijing State
Security Bureau and was accused of breaking martial law, instigated
propaganda and violating the terms of his tourist visa, Carlson said.
   ``We reject all the allegations,'' Carlson said. ``They're mad at
the messenger.''
   Hopkins was the second VOA reporter and the fourth American
journalist ordered out of the country since the June 3-4 military
crackdown against pro-democracy protesters in Beijing. A total of
seven foreign journalists have been ordered expelled from China.
   VOA Beijing Bureau Chief Alan Pessin was given three days to
leave China June 14 for violating martial law, which virtually
prohibits news reporting in Beijing, and spreading rumors and
propaganda against China.
   John Pomfret, a Beijing-based correspondent from The Associated
Press, and a reporter from the Dallas Morning News also have been
expelled from China.
   Hopkins, a former VOA bureau chief in Beijing, works in the
shortwave radio network's bureau in Boston, and is on temporary
assignment in China.
   Carlson said Chinese authorities have been jamming VOA broadcasts
into China since May 21.
</TEXT>
