<FIRST>r w PM-Veterans-Doctors     07-08 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Veterans-Doctors,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Credentials of VA Physicians Not Being Checked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnam Veterans group says people with
service-connected disabilities should be able to get government-paid
care from the doctor of their choice because VA hospitals are
falling down on the job.
   The 35,000-member Vietnam Veterans of America issued the call
Friday after details of a draft report by the General Accounting
Office critical of the Department of Veterans Affairs was published
in The Washington Post.
   The report by the government watchdog agency said officials were
unable to prove they had checked the licenses of more than half the
doctors the VA hired between 1986 and 1988.
   ``If the government is unable to provide acceptable health care
through the veterans hospital system, then these veterans should
have the right to seek medical treatment elsewhere,'' Mary R. Stout,
president of the veterans group, said in a statement.
   In its statement, the Vietnam Veterans group referred as well to
a report of high mortality rates at VA hospitals. The new report
also noted that some medical residents at the nation's 172 VA
hospitals had criminal arrest records that went unreported.
   The Department of Veterans Affairs disputed the reasoning used by
the Vietnam Veterans group.
   ``Any attempt to connect the mortality review or the GAO report
with the quality of care is totally inappropriate,'' said
spokeswoman Donna St. John, explaining that mortality rates fail to
reflect the condition of the patients who enter a particular
hospital. Hospices, for example, have reported 100 percent rates.
   She noted the GAO report, according to the Post, said: ``The
conditions cited do not mean that the medical services provided by
the VA are substandard or that VA physicians are incompetent.''
   The study was requested by Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska,
ranking minority member of the Senate Veterans' Affairs Committee.
His staff said it could not release a copy of the report because it
was in draft form. The VA said it could not release the draft
report, either.
   The full report, with VA comment, is due for release in August.
   Murkowski wrote a 1985 law telling the VA to act on problems at
hospitals after the American Medical Association found 87 doctors
with revoked, suspended or restricted licenses who were working for
the agency.
   VA officials said they could prove they had checked the licenses
of only 105 of the 207 physicians hired from 1986 to 1988, the draft
report said. The report also said the VA had not fulfilled promises
to ensure that its doctors are qualified to practice their
particular specialties.
   A further problem was detected with medical residents who work at
VA hospitals, according to the draft report. The government watchdog
agency said a records check with the FBI found that 165 of the
16,756 residents had been charged with criminal offenses between the
early 1970s and May 1987, the Post reported.
   Among the more serious offenses were 68 charged with drunken
driving and 67 charged with drug violations, five with vandalism and
five with burglary. The records did not indicate how many charges
led to convictions.
</TEXT>
