<FIRST>r w PM-AT&amp;TContract     07-08 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AT&amp;T Contract,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T Workers Overwhelmingly Approve Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of AT&amp;T's two unions will take part in
the company's first profit-sharing plan for union workers under new
contracts ratified by the workers.
   The Communications Workers of America and the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers said Friday the contracts were
ratified by ``huge margins'' in secret balloting by every bargaining
unit nationwide.
   The unions did not provide a breakdown on the voting.
   The three-year contracts, which call for varying pay raises and a
package of family-related benefits, cover an estimated 140,000
workers at American Telephone &amp; Telegraph.
   The unions, which negotiated jointly with the company for the
first time, are negotiating separate contracts with the regional
telephone companies spawned by the 1984 AT&amp;T breakup. Those
contracts expire over the next month.
   AT&amp;T spokesman Herb Linnen called the agreements ``the most
progressive ... we've ever negotiated as a company.''
   Tentative agreement on the pacts was reached May 28, several
hours after the prior contracts were to expire.
   The contracts give operations employees _ primarily operators,
technicians and clerical and administrative staff _ a 4 percent pay
increase immediately, a 2.5 percent boost next year and a 2.25
percent raise in the final year of the contract.
   AT&amp;T manufacturing workers are due an 8 percent lump sum payment
immediately after ratification; those in skilled trades will also
get a 50-cents-an-hour pay raise. All manufacturing workers will get
a 3.5 percent base wage increase next year and a 3 percent raise in
the final year.
   The formula for the profit-sharing plan should provide each AT&amp;T
worker about $700 in the first year of the contract, based on the
company's 1988 earnings, according to company and union officials.
   Other features of the contracts include a $5 million fund to
expand child-care opportunities for union workers and a series of
new or expanded leave policies for union workers who become parents
or who have a sick child or parent.
   The unions and AT&amp;T also reached agreement on steps designed to
curb the company's rising health care costs and agreed to work with
other interested parties in encouraging government efforts in that
area.
</TEXT>
