<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CanadianProtest 2ndLd-Writethru a0744 07-08 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canadian Protest, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0744,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada Protests U.S. Seizure of Fishing Trawlers</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: SUBS 15th graf, `The Viscount..., to CORRECT relationship of
masters to boats; picks up 16th graf, `The United ...</UNK>
<DATELINE>KETCHIKAN, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court complaint alleging
illegal fishing was filed Friday against two Canadian vessels seized
off southeast Alaska, and the crews were to return to Canada without
their boats.
   Canada, meanwhile, filed a protest with the State Department in
Washington, D.C., demanding release of the boats seized by the U.S.
Coast Guard in waters claimed by the United States southeast of
Ketchikan.
   Mark Davis, acting U.S. attorney for Alaska, filed the complaint
in U.S. District Court at Anchorage, citing violations of the
federal Magnuson Act. The complaint seeks forfeiture of the vessels,
the gear and the fish on board.
   The 4,000 pounds of salmon aboard each boat was sold to a
Ketchikan cannery Friday and the proceeds were to be held by the
court pending resolution of the complaint, officials said.
   No criminal action was planned against the crew members, said
Timothy Burgess, an assistant U.S. attorney in Anchorage. ``This
action is only against the vessels themselves,'' he said.
   Mike Harpold, a federal immigration agent in Ketchikan, said the
crew members avoided immigration charges by voluntarily returning to
Canada. The four men and three women were to leave Ketchikan late
Friday night.
   The crews had been held on their boats at the Ketchikan Coast
Guard base since Wednesday, Coast Guard spokesman Ed Moreth said
from Juneau.
   The vessels were escorted to Ketchikan after they were boarded
Wednesday in disputed waters. Burgess said the boats were first seen
fishing in undisputed U.S. waters north of the Canadian-claimed
boundary.
   Malcolm McKechnie, a spokesman for the Canadian Embassy in
Washington, said his government issued a verbal protest over the
incident Wednesday and delivered a formal diplomatic protest note to
the State Department Friday.
   ``We would like to see the immediate release of the vessels and
their crews,'' McKechnie said.
   He said the boats, the Viscount and the Fonzie, were seized after
a ``hot pursuit'' in disputed waters. Because jurisdiction over the
area is disputed, ``we believe there should be restraint
exercised,'' McKechnie said.
   ``What took place was a divergence from the normal practice of
restraint,'' he said.
   The Coast Guard said the Canadian vessels were found fishing
illegally in U.S. waters of Dixon Entrance, between Southeast Alaska
and Canada's Queen Charlotte Islands.
   The Coast Guard said the cutter Cape Hatteras found the boats
fishing about one-quarter mile north of the Dixon Entrance boundary
that Canada claims.
   The Viscount was carrying a crew of four and was under the
supervision of master Bruce Devereau of Vancouver, British Columbia.
Howard Wilson of Parksville, British Columbia, was master of the
Fonzie, which had three crew members.
   The United States and Canada have not agreed on fishing
boundaries in the area involved, despite efforts at negotiations
since 1903.
   Moreth said it is the first time Canadian fishing vessels have
been detained off Alaska in the last couple of years.
   Devereux told Canadian Press his vessel was boarded in Canadian
waters and he was roughed up. Coast Guardsmen jumped aboard the
Viscount without permission and ``threatened to use whatever force
was necessary'' to take the the boat into port, he said Friday.
   Devereux said two Coast Guardsmen came aboard and slammed him
against a stove with a club. Crewman Brad Dean was briefly
handcuffed, he said.
   Another crew member, Dianne Cheadle, protested Devereux's
treatment.
   ``I said, `Hey, you can't do this. He's the skipper, he's got
control of this boat,''' Cheadle said.
   Moreth said none of the crew members had filed complaints about
their treatment. ``We did get information that the captain of the
Viscount was very uncooperative,'' he said.
