<HEAD>Fired Employee Shots Supervisors, Killing One</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with five grafs to recast. Picks up 5th graf, `A caller...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fired plant worker shot two of his
supervisors, killing one of them, and briefly took a co-worker
hostage at a Coca-Cola plant late Friday, police said.
   The worker, identified as 45-year-old John Wallace, was believed
to be holed up in the Coca-Cola Distribution Center after releasing
the hostage unharmed late Friday.
   Cobb County Police Chief Culver Johnson said Wallace came to work
at the plant in this Atlanta suburb shortly before 10 p.m. and was
told of his dismissal. The reason for his firing was not immediately
known.
   Witnesses told police Wallace went to clean out his locker and
returned armed with a small handgun and fired on some workers,
shooting two of them.
   A caller telephoned WSB-TV in Atlanta and identified himself as
Wallace, telling reporters he had shot two men and was holding a
hostage. Police said station officials acted as negotiators by
telephone until police took over. Part of the telephone conversation
was televised.
   Asked by WSB whom he had shot, the caller said, ``Two men'' but
said later he wasn't sure if they were dead.
   Although the first victim was removed about a half-hour after the
shooting, the other was not moved until 11:15 p.m. and died on the
scene.
   The victims' names were not released Friday night.
   Police said Wallace then took one man hostage for more than an
hour after the shootings, but that man was released shortly after
the slain victim was brought out.
   Officials at Kennestone Hospital in Marietta said the second
shooting victim was in serious condition.
