<FIRST>r w PM-OSHA-Ford     07-08 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OSHA-Ford,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Proposes $1.9 Million Fine Against Ford Subsidiary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is seeking nearly $2 million in
fines from a Ford Motor Co. subsidiary that allegedly failed to
properly record injuries and illnesses in violation of an agreement
reached with the automaker two years ago.
   Ford Electronics and Refrigeration Corp. of Lansdale, Pa., has 15
working days to contest the fine proposed Friday by the Occupational
Safety and Health Administration.
   OSHA said the company had willfully ignored a 1987 agreement
between the agency and Ford in which the automaker settled
worker-safety complaints at two other plants and agreed to a
company-wide reform of its record keeping practices relating to
illnesses and injuries.
   A Ford spokesman said company officials were reviewing the
citations and had no immediate comment.
   The Pennsylvania subsidiary was cited for 241 willful violations
of the agreement for allegedly misrecording or failing to record
injuries and illnesses. It also was cited for serious violations for
allegedly overexposing workers to the hazards of lasers and
repetitive motion.
   ``Other employers who enter into agreements with OSHA to abate
job safety and health violations and hazards should realize that
this case shows we mean business about enforcing settlement
agreements,'' Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole said in announcing the
proposed fine.
   The action stems from OSHA inspections of the Lansdale plant that
began earlier this year following an employee complaint about
exposure to asbestos, OSHA said. The agency said the plant employs
about 2,600 workers and manufactures auto parts such as cruise
control units and fuel injection systems.
   Willful violations are defined as situations in which the
employer knew of a violation of OSHA standards or was aware that a
hazardous condition existed but made no attempt to correct it.
Serious violations cover alleged offenses in which the employer knew
or should have known a workplace activity posed a substantial
probability of death or serious physical harm.
   If Ford contests the fine, the case would be referred to an
administrative law judge, who would hold hearings on the matter. If
either side appeals a judge's finding, the case is referred to the
quasi-judicial Occupational Safety and Health Review Commission. Any
appeals from that proceeding would go to the U.S. Court of Appeals.
</TEXT>
