<FIRST>r w PM-B-2Test     07-08 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-B-2 Test,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Announces B-2 Flight Test This Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The long-awaited test flight of the B-2 stealth
bomber will be held later this month, the Pentagon has announced.
   The outdoor tests and flight will be held during a 15-day period
beginning Sunday, the Pentagon said Friday.
   The controversial plane, manufactured by Northrop Corp., has been
undergoing a final check at an Air Force plant in Palmdale, Calif.
It has been described as the most radical and expensive bomber ever
built and has become the target of Capitol Hill budget cutters.
   Critics in Congress oppose paying the bill for planes, which
could cost between $500 million and $750 million each, before the
first plane has ever gotten off the ground. The Air Force already
has invested $22 billion in the program, expected to cost taxpayers
a total of $70 billion.
   The B-2 has no sharp angles or conventional fuselage and relies
on the radar-absorbing coatings on its surface to avoid detection.
   During the 15-day period, the plane is expected to be rolled out
of its hangar and undergo a series of dress rehearsal tests that
include turning on its engines, slow- and high-speed taxi tests on
the runway, and a full flight test.
   For its initial flight, the Air Force will take the plane from
Palmdale for a test flight expected to last about 2{ hours, landing
at Edwards Air Force Base about 40 miles away, said Air Force
spokeswoman Capt. Tess Taft. The tests may take several days.
   ``Only after it looks perfect, and everything looks right, will
they take it up,'' Taft said, explaining the 15-day test window.
   While the news media will be allowed to observe the outdoor
tests, the public is not invited, the Pentagon said. The specific
date and time of the tests will not be announced, but the media will
be told by mid morning if no tests are scheduled for a particular
day.
   The Air Force will hold a news conference after the first flight,
the statement said.
   While the B-2 has not been operationally tested in the field,
individual systems have been tried. The Air Force says the B-2 will
not be deployed before 1991.
</TEXT>
