<HEAD>President To Offer English Teachers To Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is prepared to offer to send
English teachers to Hungary when he visits Budapest next week, a
move that would be establish the first informal U.S. Peace Corps
mission to a European country.
   U.S. officials said Friday that the project is part of a package
of proposals Bush is examining as he prepares to travel to Poland
and Hungary.
   He mostly will offer economic assistance, provided government
leaders in Poland and Hungary commit themselves to austerity
programs, according to the officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The programs would accelerate U.S. cultural and business ties
with the Soviet bloc nations as they open up their political
systems. Hungary, in particular, has been moving its Marxist economy
toward a free-market system.
   Bush, who leaves for Poland on Sunday, is visiting the East
European countries on his way to a seven-nation economic summit
meeting in Paris.
   Hungary two years ago suspended Russian as a compulsory language
in schools. The U.S. hope is that English will become more common.
   Poland, which carries the burden of a $36 billion debt, is hoping
for financial aid.
   A senior U.S. official, briefing reporters at the White House,
dismissed reports that Warsaw expected $10 billion in U.S. or
Western help. But he left open the possibility of a more modest
economic program, which Bush would coordinate with the leaders of
Britain, Canada, France, Italy, Japan and West Germany at the
economic summit.
