<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CivilRights-Education     07-08 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Civil Rights-Education,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Restores Important Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civil rights group says a ruling by a federal
appeals court that the Education Department may be sued to seek
stricter enforcement of laws is an important step toward reviving a
major civil rights case.
   A panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia on Friday reversed a lower court's ruling that students in
18 states lacked legal standing to bring the case to speed up
desegregation of public schools and state colleges.
   On the basis of his 1987 ruling, U.S. District Judge John H.
Pratt had dissolved two 1983 orders that set timetables for the
Education Department's review of desegregation plans submitted by
states for public schools and universities.
   In Friday's ruling, a three-judge panel held the plaintiffs had a
``direct stake in the effective enforcement of anti-discrimination
laws'' because they were enrolled in schools, colleges or
universities ``that engaged in proscribed discrimination.''
   ``Plaintiffs in this action, beyond question, are the intended
beneficiaries of the statutes under which they sue'' and could prove
a direct harm if the laws are not enforced, the panel ruled in an
opinion by Judge Ruth B. Ginsburg.
   While the court did not issue a final judgment in the case
pending resolution of other significant legal issues, the decision
was hailed by the NAACP Legal Defense and Education Fund, Inc., as
an important step toward reviving the case.
   ``It's very crucial that the courts have upheld our right to sue
under these civil rights statutes,'' said Janell M. Byrd, an
attorney for the New York-based organization.
   ``Judge Pratt's ruling would have closed the door not only on
this litigation, it would make it very difficult to sue the federal
government for failure to enforce a statute,'' she said.
   The suit, which dates back to the Nixon administration, produced
court decisions by Pratt ordering the government to revoke federal
aid to segregated schools and universities under the 1964 Civil
Rights Act.
   It resulted in a series of court orders and a 1977 consent decree
under which the Department of Health, Education and Welfare, and
later the Department of Education, were given timetables for
reviewing discrimination complaints and later plans for ending the
last vestiges of segregation.
   The Reagan administration sought in 1982 to dissolve the 1977
consent decree, saying it could not be legally bound by an agreement
entered into by the Carter administration.
   That issue is now before the appeals court along with several
others that remain as legal hurdles for civil rights lawyers seeking
to revive the case.
   The case involved enforcement of desegregation laws against
schools and universities in Alabama, Arkansas, Delaware, Florida,
Georgia, Kentucky, Louisiana, Maryland, Mississippi, Missouri, North
Carolina, Ohio, Oklahoma, Pennsylvania, South Carolina, Virginia,
West Virginia, and Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
