<DOCNO> AP890708-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-YellowstonePreparations Bjt   07-08 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yellowstone Preparations, Bjt,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yellowstone Firefighters Ready For Fire Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Once burned, twice shy, goes the adage, and
Yellowstone National Park officials who watched their forest go up
in smoke last year are ready to douse any blaze at a moment's notice.
   A year after massive fires charred nearly half of the park, its
administrators have beefed up fire crews, obtained a new helicopter
and other gear. They are determined not to allow a wet spring lull
them.
   They are armed as well with a new federal mandate to squelch
fires in the nation's forests.
   ``We could have four to five crews (80 to 100 people) on a fire
line within four to five hours if it is warranted,'' park
spokeswoman Sandy Robinson said this week in a telephone interview.
``That's excellent response time.''
   No substantial fires have been reported in Yellowstone this
summer, but just 150 miles to the south of the park a 2,400-acre
fire was burning Friday in the Bridger-Teton National Forest, and
there were out-of-control wildfires in Utah and California.
   Under a policy begun in 1972, Yellowstone crews in previous years
let naturally caused fires burn unless they threatened people or
structures.
   But last year, more than 200 fires seared an estimated 1.3
million acres of the park and surrounding national forests,
radically altering the face of the most venerated national park.
   Last month, the Interior Department announced it was suspending
the let-burn policies in national parks and forests.
   In addition, it ordered a moratorium on controlled, or limited
fires. George Berklacy, a spokesman for the National Park Service,
said at the time that he doubted the moratorium would be lifted this
summer.
   One hundred park employees are ready to leave their jobs as
naturalists, security guards and rangers and head into the
Yellowstone backcountry to tackle fires, Robinson said.
   Three lookout towers have been manned since June 15 at
Yellowstone and will be staffed until Sept. 30, with a fourth tower
staffed on a part-time basis, Robinson said.
   ``All reports of smoke are being checked out,'' she said.
   Several false alarms turned out to be dust devils or steam rising
from thermal areas, she said.
   While the 2.2 million-acre park in the northwest corner of
Wyoming has enjoyed a relatively wet spring and early summer, record
high temperatures this weekend may signal the beginning of the fire
season, Robinson said.
   ``We always have a high degree of preparedness,'' Robinson said.
``We are more prepared this year in part due to the firefighting
efforts of last year.''
   Hundreds of firefighters were marshaled to battle last year's
blazes while a debate raged among naturalists and government
administrators on whether the policy to let the fires burn made
sense.
   The park has added a helicopter and now has two of the craft to
dump water on fires, and a six-person crew trained for a chopper
assault on any fire that flares up, Robinson said.
   An extra 75 to 80 employees have been trained to fight fires,
giving Yellowstone 275 employees with red cards _ the firefighting
certificate, Robinson said.
   ``We have 100 that are already outfitted, that we can call out
immediately,'' she said.
   Yellowstone also has 100 new chain saws and two new water pumps.
   Robinson said the park itself is better prepared for the 1989
fire season because last summer's fires consumed much of the
available dead wood and created natural fire lines; fire that
reaches recently burned areas burns itself out.
   Park firefighters already have had one chance to test their
preparedness.
   On June 14, a small fire caused by a spark from a cleanup
operation burned one-tenth of an acre at Craig Pass, southeast of
Old Faithful. A crew drove to the site, rappeled down the slope and
doused the fire with hand tools and bags of water.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890708-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0344EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BuildingUnderground Bjt   07-08 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Building Underground, Bjt,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Promotes Benefits Of Underground Construction</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MP1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businesses looking to expand in congested
cities like New York, Chicago and San Francisco usually turn to
skyscrapers or the suburbs, but a group of engineers and architects
says a better solution lies just below the surface.
   Building underground has the potential to provide millions of
square feet of clean, energy-efficient space in the nation's major
cities, according to the American Underground-Space Association.
   ``Underground has the benefit of allowing greater density in
urban areas and mitigating the need for sprawl,'' Susan Nelson, the
group's executive director, said in a recent interview. ``You save
land doing that, you save energy and transportation, and you just
create a more vital city center.''
   Getting that message across, however, has proven to be difficult
for the Minneapolis-based, non-profit organization.
   ``Visibility really is a major problem with underground
construction,'' Nelson acknowledges. ``I think you'll find that many
architects aren't interested in it because they like to make a
statement. It's hard to make a statement underground.''
   Since it was founded in 1976, the association has been touting
the benefits of underground facilities to business and government
leaders and helping exchange information among professionals
interested in the idea. The group now has 400 members in 39 states
and 25 countries.
   Subterranean buildings are ideal for researchers and
industrialists who need clean work environments because few airborne
pollutants can invade the underground, Nelson said.
   They also save energy because the ground offers protection from
cold winter winds and the hot summer sun, but energy concerns have
waned along with the price of oil in recent years.
   ``I think there was more activity in the late '70s when we were
more concerned about energy,'' Nelson said. ``I think it's a matter
of not being presented with the idea.''
   To help remedy that, the association recently published a book
titled ``Groundworks'' featuring 15 underground projects built in
North America during the 1980s.
   They include the Law Library Addition at the University of
Michigan in Ann Arbor, all three stories of which are below ground;
the Smithsonian Institution Museum Complex in Washington, D.C.,
which is 96 percent below ground and extends 60 feet below the
surface; and the Civil and Mineral Engineering Building at the
University of Minnesota, which is 95 percent below ground and goes
down 110 feet.
   Also featured is the Minnesota Correctional Facility, a
maximum-security prison in suburban Oak Park Heights.
   The five-story prison's exterior walls are almost completely
earth-covered, minimizing its visibility and providing another
barrier to escape, said Assistant Warden James Crawford.
   Crawford said he has heard no complaints from prisoners or
employees at the 7-year-old facility.
   ``They have access to the outside,'' he said of the 400 inmates.
``Of course, all of their cells have windows'' facing a central
courtyard.
   Not surprisingly, Nelson's own office is located in a so-called
earth-bermed building near downtown Minneapolis. The four-story
building's first floor is built below ground, and earth has been
built up to cover the second and third floors on two sides of the
building.
   Misconceptions are holding back more widespread use of
underground space, Nelson contends.
   ``There is the myth out there that it is very expensive,'' she
said. Cost depends on the difficulty of digging in a particular
spot, and in some places it's inexpensive, she said.
   ``There's also a psychological aspect,'' Nelson said. ``I think
they feel they will be claustrophobic. They don't like the idea of
no windows. But you can work in a skyscraper and never walk past a
window during the day.
   ``I think the expectation of being underground is quite different
from the reality. People who work underground generally like it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890708-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0348EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-08 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Honors Little League, Little Leaguers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President and former baseball coach George Bush
took time out from preparations for his upcoming trip to communist
Europe to talk baseball with 4,000 Little Leaguers.
   ``In Little League, all that matters is the size of your heart
and of your dreams,'' he told the youths Friday.
   Bush and the young players, wearing uniforms identifying them as
Indians, Mets, Springfield, Rocco's Rockettes, and Parkland Blue
Jays, met on the South Lawn to mark the founding of Little League 50
years ago in Williamsport, Pa.
   Baseball greats such as Stan Musial, Mike Schmidt, Brooks
Robinson, Gary Carter, Ted Sizemore, Joe Morgan and Jim Palmer also
attended the ceremony.
   The president repeated a line that Babe Ruth delivered to a crowd
in Yankee Stadium when he was dying of cancer:
   ``You know, the only real game in the world, I think, is
baseball. You've got to start from way down when you are 6 or 7
years old and if you try hard enough you're bound to come out on
top.''
   With those words, said the president, Ruth ``defined why Little
League baseball has become an American, indeed, an international
institution.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Crowe: US-Soviet Ties May Be Unsettled For Long Period</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adm. William J. Crowe, retiring head of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, says his historic 11-day visit to the Soviet
Union revealed the superpowers are entering a period of ``uneasy
transition.''
   Crowe, in a speech Friday before the National Press Club, said
such circumstances do ``not ... make me feel comfortable.''
   He said he hopes the two military giants are moving toward a new
era in the superpower relationship, but ``to conclude that we are
already there would be a serious mistake.''
   The 64-year-old admiral, speaking a day after President Bush
rejected a new call from Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev for
talks to eliminate short-range nuclear missiles in Europe, said he
believes U.S. should avoid ``dramatic counter-responses'' to Kremlin
initiatives ``at this point.''
   Crowe met for more than an hour with Gorbachev two weeks ago in
Moscow during his precedent-setting tour of once-secret Soviet
military installations and visits with Soviet military officers.
   It was the first formal visit of a Joint Chiefs chairman to the
Soviet Union and was the latest in a series of high-level visits
designed to dispel distrust between the superpowers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Lawmakers Says Government Will Buy $15 Million Worth Of Apples</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Agriculture will buy $15
million worth of apples in an effort to help reduce a huge surplus
created when consumers stopped buying amid fears over use of the
chemical Alar.
   The industry has estimated that 5 million to 7 million boxes of
apples from last year's crop, valued at between $40 million and $56
million, remain unsold.
   The department Friday said apple stocks were 53 percent greater
on May 31 than the average for that date for the previous three
years, and prices to growers had fallen by $3 to $4 per carton from
what they were a year ago.
   The top grade of red apples produced in Washington state were
recently selling for between $7.50 and $8 per box, about $2 below
the cost of production. The nation's 20,000 apple growers have
estimated losses at well over $100 million in sales.
   Alar is used to enhance red color, to ease harvesting by delaying
ripening so that most apples ripen together, and to lengthen shelf
and storage life. The chemical penetrates throughout the fruit
tissue and cannot be washed off like many pesticides.
   The Alar controversy began in late February when a private
environmental advocacy group, the Natural Resources Defense Council,
said apples treated with the chemical substantially increase the
risk of cancer in children.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Oil-Eating Microorganisms May Munch on Alaskan Oil Spill</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmental Protection Agency officials say
they are optimistic that oil-eating microorganisms may soon become
valuable tools in cleaning up the Exxon oil spill in Alaska.
   Preliminary findings from an experiment in which nutrients were
used to enhance the growth of such organisms on small sections of
Alaska's contaminated beaches appear to show success, EPA
Administrator William Reilly said Friday.
   In some cases, the number of organisms multiplied 100-fold only a
week into the experiment, and even in the early stages some beaches
treated with nutrients showed ``a striking disappearance of the oil
from rock surfaces,'' the EPA said.
   Reilly said that the results were ``potentially good news'' and
that if the preliminary findings hold up, Exxon Corp. may begin
later this summer to treat large sections of beach with nutrients to
enhance oil-eating microorganism growth.
   Eric Brathauer, assistant administrator for research and
development, said it will be several weeks before some remaining
questions about the experiment will be resolved.
</TEXT>
