<HEAD>Batman Suit Stolen, Then Recovered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 24 hours this week, Batman must have
hoped no menaces threatened the good citizens of Gotham City.
   Otherwise, he would have had to answer the call of duty in his
Batbriefs.
   On Thursday, some dastardly bad-guy entered the Please Touch
Museum for children in Philadelphia and stole Batman's costume _ the
original one worn by Adam West during the 1960s hit television
series. Detectives said the costume is valued at $50,000.
   But evil never triumphs over superheroes.
   About 3 p.m. Friday, police in suburban Upper Dublin Township
stopped a vehicle with the undamaged costume in its trunk. An
anonymous tip led authorities to the car.
   Philadelphia police Sgt. Edward Geigert said the driver,
19-year-old John Spitalik of Blairsville was charged with receiving
stolen property. Other charges are pending, Geigert said.
   Spitalik told police he didn't steal the costume, he bought it.
   From some Joker, no doubt.
