<HEAD>With PM-HUD Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>OMB Seeks Reports on Cabinet Efforts to Fight Fraud and Abuse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Office of Management and Budget wants all
Cabinet departments and two major agencies to report on what they're
doing to fight fraud and abuse.
   An OMB memorandum to the 14 departments, the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration and the Environmental Protection Agency on
June 27 asked for reports by July 23, OMB spokeswoman Barbara Clay
said Friday.
   The memo from Budget Director Richard Darman was issued as
reports of wide-ranging fraud, mismanagement and abuse at the
Department of Housing and Urban Development mounted. It was
disclosed in today's editions of The Washington Post.
   ``I wouldn't want you to look at this as arising from the
troubles at HUD,'' said Clay.
   ``I would call it a concern that recommendations made by the
government's own inspectors, the inspectors general, might not be
being followed up,'' she said.
   The HUD inspector general told a congressional hearing on June 30
that on five occasions Congress and the department ignored his
warnings. The inspector general, Paul A. Adams, said the warnings
began in 1985.
