<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0450EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Voyager-Neptune     07-08 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Voyager-Neptune,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neptune's Third Moon Discovered By Approaching Voyager 2 Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seeking new worlds 2.75 billion miles
from Earth, NASA'S Voyager 2 spacecraft discovered a third moon
orbiting Neptune and is likely to find many more, scientists say.
   ``It's nice, after years of preparation for the Neptune
encounter, to have Voyager now starting to make these discoveries,''
Jet Propulsion Laboratory astronomer Steve Synnott said Friday.
``Ninety-nine-point-nine percent of the time this discovery process
is frustration, so it is finally nice to dig a nugget out of all the
mud.''
   Synnott detected the moon, temporarily designated 1989 N1, in
photographs taken by one of the space probe's television cameras.
Previously, only two moons had been detected from earth.
   Project scientist Ellis Miner said recently that Voyager might
discover at least 10 small moons orbiting Neptune.
   Voyagers 1 and 2 _ with total mission costs of $865 million _ now
have discovered at least 18 moons: three at Jupiter, at least four
and possibly seven at Saturn, 10 orbiting Uranus, and one so far at
Neptune.
   That boosts the total lunar count to 16 for Jupiter, at least 17
for Saturn, 15 for Uranus and three for Neptune.
   Synnott, who helped discover several of those moons, was asked
how he celebrates when he finds an entire new world.
   ``I usually go home and have a beer,'' he said.
   The Jet Propulsion laboratory operates America's unmanned space
exploration program for the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration.
   Voyager 2 was launched from Florida in 1977, explored Jupiter in
1979, Saturn in 1981 and Uranus in 1986. Today it was 2.67 billion
miles from Earth and 42.8 million miles from Neptune, speeding at
42,200 mph toward its Aug. 24 close encounter with the solar
system's fourth-largest planet.
   Voyager will be 2.75 billion miles from Earth when it sweeps
3,000 miles above Neptune's north pole cloudtops at midnight EDT
Aug. 24, but its curving path to Neptune will equal 4.43 billion
miles.
   Neptune's other moons are Nereid and the backward-orbiting
Triton, discovered through telescopes on Earth in 1949 and 1846,
respectively.
   In 1981, scientists using telescopes believed they detected
another Neptunian moon, but its existence hasn't yet been confirmed
by Voyager.
   With a diameter estimated at 125 to 400 miles, 1989 N1 is smaller
than Nereid _ estimated at 190 to 620 miles across _ or Triton, with
an estimated diameter of 1,400 to 2,240 miles, or roughly the size
of Earth's moon.
   Synnott first detected the moon as a smudge in images taken by
Voyager 2 on June 21. He confirmed the discovery Wednesday by
examining images.
   ``I never really jumped and screamed, but I clenched my fist,
nodded my head to myself and said, `Yup, that one's real!''' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
