<FIRST>r a PM-BlackMattie     07-08 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Mattie,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who's Been In Louisiana Prison Longest Getting Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louisiana's longest-held inmate welcomed his
parole and said 41 years in prison had made him a different man.
   ``I learned to pick my people and stay out of trouble,'' James
``Black Mattie'' Robertson said. ``I'm a church-going man now. I
want to go out and be a good citizen now.''
   Robertson will leave the Louisiana State Penitentiary in Angola
on Monday, corrections officials said.
   ``All factors indicate that he is no longer a danger to
society,'' the state Parole Board said in granting Robertson parole
on Friday.
   The 67-year-old prisoner has been in the prison since 1948,
serving a life sentence for raping the wife of a sawmill worker in
rural Tensas Parish.
   He was turned down for parole in March 1988. When he reapplied
this year, the parole board ordered psychological testing before
considering his application.
   ``I never got discouraged,'' he said in a telephone interview
after hearing the news. ``When they turned me down that first time
they said I hadn't given them enough time. They said, `Give us some
more.' So I did.''
   The parole board assigned him to a halfway house in Baton Rouge
for six months where he will receive counseling to help him adjust
to a life of freedom.
   Robert Steele Sr., a businessman in a New Orleans suburb, has
promised him a job and place to live.
   ``He's welcome here. He's a fine man. I got to know him about a
year ago and I can tell you he should have been out of prison a long
time ago,'' Steele said.
   ``I'm kind of nervous from being in here so long, but there's a
lot I want to do. I want to see my boy and my grandchildren. I've
got their pictures, but I've never seen them,'' Robertson said.
   He said he hasn't seen his son Robert, who lives in Ferriday, for
10 or 15 years, although they have stayed in touch.
   Robertson's prison job is to keep clean the sidewalks around the
administration buildings of the sprawling prison. But for most of
his prison years he worked the farmland that covers Angola's fields,
which is how he got his nickname.
   Inmates and guards called the old train that once hauled sugar
cane out of the prison ``Mattie,'' Robertson said. The guards said
Robertson worked as hard as the train so they started calling him
Mattie, too.
   ``I used to holler just like that train. That's what I did again
today when they told me I was going to leave here. I hollered real
loud. Now this Mattie is pulling out of here and he won't be back.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
