<FIRST>r a PM-North-Republicans     07-08 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North-Republicans,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oliver North Says He's Not Waiting For Presidential Pardon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Contra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House aide Oliver North, spared
prison when he was sentenced this week on charges stemming from the
Iran-Contra affair, isn't relying on a possible presidential pardon.
   ``I don't think much about that. We're going to press the appeal,
and I'm confident in the outcome,'' North said at a closed
fund-raising session in Tampa Friday.
   And in his first public appearance since being sentenced
Wednesday, North also spoke to about 400 young Republicans in
Orlando.
   He told them he would not rule out a run for Congress, though he
acknowledged his conviction on felony counts prevents his holding
federal office.
   North said he first has to overcome ``tremendous legal problems''
from the scandal, adding that he had other worries as well.
   ``I deeply believe my first responsiblity is to my family, which
is still at risk from Abu Nidal and the Arab terrorists and the
Libyans, both of whom have offered to take me out,'' he told members
of the College Republicans National Committee.
   North, 45, received a three-year suspended sentence, was fined
$150,000 and ordered to perform 1,200 hours of community service for
his role in the Reagan administration's secret scheme to arm the
Contras. He will spend two years on probation.
   Asked if he would have done anything differently in helping the
Contras, North said:
   ``I deeply believe many people could have done much more to
explain the cause of Nicaraguan resistance so that we wouldn't have
had the on-again, off-again, up-again, down-again situation in
Washington that has been so despicable to those people.''
   North was received warmly.
   ``He did absolutely nothing with any criminal intent,'' said
Susan Brackin, the Republican group's executive director. ``Of
course we're very, very relieved that Col. North will not be
spending any time in jail.
   ``It would be a complete disgrace for what we consider a national
hero to have to spend time in prison.''
   But a group of protesters from the Central Florida Coalition for
Peace marched outside the Orlando hotel where North spoke.
   ``We were very upset when we heard Oliver North would not be
receiving any serious sentence after being found guilty ... on
felony counts of lying to Congress and basically subverting the
United States Constitution,'' coalition head Bruce Gagnon said.
   North was convicted May 4 of obstructing a congressional
investigation, destroying documents and illegally accepting a
gratuity. He was acquitted on nine other charges.
</TEXT>
