<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0420EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China     07-08 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Expels Another American Reporter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese authorities today ordered the expulsion of
another American reporter, the fourth U.S. journalist told to leave
the country since last month.
   Mark Hopkins, correspondent for the U.S. government-run Voice of
America radio network, was given 72 hours to leave China, VOA
Director Richard W. Carlson said in a telephone interview from
Washington.
   Hopkins was the second VOA reporter ordered out of the country
since the bloody June 3-4 military crackdown against pro-democracy
protesters in Beijing. A total of seven foreign journalists have
been ordered expelled from China.
   Hopkins, 58, was called in this morning to the Beijing State
Security Bureau and accused of breaking martial law, instigating
propaganda, and violating the terms of his tourist visa, Carlson
said.
   ``We reject all the allegations,'' Carlson said. ``They're mad at
the messenger.''
   VOA Beijing Bureau Chief Alan Pessin was given three days to
leave China June 14. He was accused of spreading rumors and
anti-Chinese propaganda and violating martial law, which virtually
prohibits news reporting in Beijing.
   John Pomfret, a Beijing-based correspondent from The Associated
Press, has also been expelled, as has Joseph Kahn, a reporter for
the Dallas Morning News.
   Hopkins, a former VOA bureau chief in Beijing, works in the
shortwave radio network's bureau in Boston. He has been on temporary
assignment in China since June 10.
   VOA broadcasts in Chinese and English to the Chinese mainland. It
estimates its listening audience in the tens of millions.
   However, Carlson said Chinese authorities have been jamming VOA
broadcasts into China since May 21.
   Now, Carlson said, ``They're trying to jam us intellectually
too.''
   Pessin and Pomfret were ordered out of China together. They were
the only two resident correspondents who were expelled.
   Three correspondents for Britain's Independent Television Network
and a Kahn, a part-time writer for the Morning News, were on tourist
visas and ordered to leave China last month.
   The Chinese press meanwhile today reported investigations into
several major corruption cases, keeping up the publicity around its
drive to root out profiteering, swindling and bribery.
   ``Down with corruption'' was one of the main rallying cries in
April and May of the pro-democracy movement for a freer society and
a cleaner government.
   Since Chinese troops used arms and tanks to put down the
uprising, the government has gone to great lengths to demonstrate
that it takes the anti-corruption call to heart. At least 300 people
died in the crackdown.
   Ten major cases of profiteering involving municipal and local
companies are being investigated in Shanghai, China's largest city
and main industrial base, the Communist Party newspaper People's
Daily said.
   The firms engaged in profiteering by reselling duty-free
materials, cars, houses, color television sets and refrigerators,
the paper said.
   The People's Daily also reported today that a swindler in rural
Shanxi province who defrauded business firms of $6.75 million was
sentenced to life in prison.
   Pei Wenzhong, chairman and general manager of the Luliang Iron
and Steel Co. and three rural factories, signed bogus contracts for
sale of fertilizer and steel with 10 companies, the paper said. He
also bribed a local policeman with $2,430, it said.
   China wound up meetings this week of its National People's
Congress, the legislature and the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference, a high-level advisory group.
   Former Chinese President Li Xiannian, chairman of the advisory
group, told delegates this week that among ousted Communist Party
chief Zhao Ziyang's mistakes was ``casting aside the basic
principles of Mao Tse-tung thought,'' according to newspaper reports
today.
   Li also accused Zhao of not applying the basic tenets of Marxism,
an error he said would take a long period of education and struggle
to eliminate, the reports said.
   Zhao, stripped of his party and government posts following the
suppression of the uprising, was accused of splitting the party,
supporting the demonstrators and fostering the political atmosphere
that originally spawned the protests.
   The charge that he spurned Mao Tse-tung thought came as a newly
published book, ``The Life of Mao Tse-tung'' received widespread
acclaim.
   Hundreds of newspapers and periodicals in China have serialized
it or carried reviews, and 250,000 volumes have been sold, the
official Xinhua News Agency said.
   It said author Quan Yanchi traveled thousands of miles
interviewing soldiers, doctors and housemaids who once worked for
the revolutionary leader and founder of communist China.
</TEXT>
