<FIRST>r a PM-HospitalMurder     07-08 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hospital Murder,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Accused of Killing Snoring Hospital Roommate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINTHROP, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 43-year-old man has been accused of
killing his hospital roommate after complaining that the man's
snoring kept disturbing his sleep.
   William Fitzmeyer is accused of either beating or strangling
Thomas V. Fowler Jr., 76, Saturday in the room they shared at
Winthrop Community Hospital.
   Fowler died three days later and, according to Winthrop police
Lt. Angelo LaMonica, an autopsy showed the cause of death was
``blunt neck trauma.''
   LaMonica said he was unsure whether Fowler died of strangulation,
beating or a combination of both.
   Lt. Michael McManus said Fitzmeyer ``had complained to the nurses
a couple of times about the noises (Fowler) was making and the
noises he was referring to was a man snoring.''
   During the initial interviews of the investigation Fitzmeyer told
police Fowler's snoring was preventing him from sleeping, LaMonica
said. But LaMonica added that Fitzmeyer denied killing the elderly
man.
   Fitzmeyer was admitted to the hospital after suffering epileptic
seizures and placed in a room with Fowler about 2 a.m. Saturday,
LaMonica said. At about 4:45 a.m. nurses discovered Fowler, who had
been wearing an oxygen mask, had been beaten around the face and
neck and ``was bloodied up,'' said LaMonica.
   LaMonica said a cord from the oxygen mask was wrapped around
Fowler's neck.
   Fitzmeyer apparently had not been taking prescribed anti-seizure
medicine, LaMonica said. But hospital nurses told police that
Fitzmeyer, an unemployed former maintenance worker, showed no signs
of violent behavior Saturday morning.
   Hospital administrators did not return a phone call from The
Associated Press Friday.
   Winthrop police were called and within several hours they
arrested Fitzmeyer for assault with intent to murder and assault and
battery on a person older than 65. Because of Fowler's death three
days later, police said they plan to seek a murder charge.
   Fitzmeyer was released from the hospital Monday and taken to his
initial arraignment at East Boston District Court. He is being held
at the Charles Street Jail on $25,000 bail pending his second
arraignment.
   Fowler had been living in a nursing home prior to his hospital
admission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
