<FIRST>r i PM-Oman-Baker     07-08 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oman-Baker,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secretary Of State Baker Arrives in Oman for Stopover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUSCAT, Oman (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III
arrived today in this Arab sultantate from Brunei for a 36-hour
stopover en route to Poland to team up with President George Bush.
   U.S. Embassy officials described the visit to Oman as ``informal,
very much of a rest trip.'' But the brief contacts he will have are
considered significant in view of the close Omani-U.S. relations and
friendly relations between Oman and Iran.
   An embassy spokesman said there would be ``no substantive talks''
when Baker sees the Deputy Prime Minister for Defense, Fahr bin
Taymour, and the Minister of State for Foreign Affairs, Yousef bin
Alawi.
   Oman, on the western side of the strategic Strait of Hormuz at
the southern tip of the Arabian Peninsula, is the first Arab state
to be visited by Baker since he took office.
   The sultanate has become the Gulf region's most active
interlocutor with Tehran in the quest for regional stability and for
reconciliation following the end of the 8-year Iran-Iraq war last
August in a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire.
   Oman provides onshore facilities for U.S. Navy warships patroling
the Gulf and the Arabian Sea.
   Sultan Qaboos, the ruler of Oman, is abroad on an extended
European tour. In December he will take over the rotating
chairmanship of the 6-state Gulf Cooperation Council alliance that
includes Bahrain, Kuwait, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab
Emirates.
   Baker will spend the afternoon sightseeing in an Arab souk, or
market. Before his departure Sunday morning, the government has
arranged for him to visit a military base outside Muscat.
</TEXT>
