<FIRST>r a PM-StoppedTrain     07-08 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stopped Train,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Trapped in Sweltering Subway Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of commuters were trapped in a
sweltering subway tunnel when a passenger pulled an emergency cord
on a jammed commuter train, and 32 people were treated for heat
exhaustion and other injuries.
   The pull of the cord brought the train to an abrupt halt as it
approached a station in the Queens borough Friday evening, and two
other trains also stopped, stranding more than 2,500 people
underground.
   It took rescuers more than 2{ hours to evacuate the trains.
   ``We saw people collapsing. Some of them collapsed right in front
of us,'' said Fire Department Lt. John B. Harden. ``There were quite
a few people sprawled on the platform.''
   The person who pulled the cord was not found, said Termaine
Garden, a Transit Authority spokesman.
   When the motorman reset the cord, the train ``would not take
power,'' he said.
   After a few minutes without power or air conditioning, ``some
passengers on board started climbing down between the cars to the
tracks,'' Garden said. Police were called in to help evacuate the
trains.
   Capt. Robert A. Hannafey of the Emergency Medical Services said
none of the injuries were life-threatening.
   Ten people were treated at the scene and 22 others were taken to
area hospitals suffering from the heat and ``minor bumps and
bruises,'' he said.
   Service on the subway line was restored about three hours after
the incident.
   Garden said the tunnels were ``very humid, very hot'' and the
temperature may have been as high as 100 degrees.
</TEXT>
