<FIRST>u i PM-WarsawPact 3rdLd-Writethru a0459 07-08 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Warsaw Pact, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0459,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets, Warsaw Pact Sign Agreement Seeking Nuclear-Free Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new grafs 7-8 to UPDATE with report Honecker ill and
returned home without taking part in signing. Picks up graf 7 pvs, `Gorbachev
expressed ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union and its Warsaw Pact
allies today signed an agreement to seek a nuclear-free Europe with
significantly fewer soldiers and arms, the official Soviet news
agency Tass reported.
   The document calls for ``a stable and secure Europe, free from
nuclear and chemical weapons, for substantial cuts in armed forces,
arms and military spending,'' Tass said.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev signed the red-covered text
of the 16-page accord with a flourish and a smile for photographers,
who were allowed to attend a brief signing ceremony. The signing
took place in a marble-columned hall in Bucharest's former royal
palace.
   In remarks Friday at a palace dinner for the East bloc's top
Communist Party and government officials, Gorbachev said the
documents adopted by the Pact in the two-day annual summit contain a
``serious palpable answer to the proposals made by the NATO
countries.''
   President Bush on May 29 called for cuts in U.S. and Soviet
troops to 275,000 soldiers each stationed in Europe outside of the
Soviet Union, and for reductions in weapons and combat aircraft.
   ``We took new steps today toward European security and
rapprochement and East-West dialogue,'' Gorbachev said.
   East German leader Erich Honecker meanwhile flew home early this
morning suffering from an illness that was serious enough for him to
miss the signing ceremony with his Warsaw Pact collegues.
   The 76-year-old leader's illness was variously described as a
gallbladder ailment by the East German news agency ADN, as ``acute
biliary trouble'' by the Romanian news agency Agerpres and as a
kidney problem by Roman officials and East German journalists in
Bucharest. Bile ducts carry digestive fluids from the liver or
gallbladder to the intestinal system.
   Gorbachev expressed the hope that the new East Bloc agreement
will allow the two military alliances in Europe to rapidly and
successfully complete negotiations for arms reductions.
   ``I think one could say that, owing to our comradely talks today,
one more serious step was taken offering prerequisites to the
further progress of the all-European process,'' Gorbachev said at
the dinner.
   Details of the documents were to be released later today.
   The Soviet leader said the pact's ``important resolution'' will
help narrow the gap between NATO and the East bloc and bring success
at the Vienna negotiations on a reduction of conventional weaponry
in Europe.
   Gorbachev's host, Romanian President Nicolae Ceausescu, told the
dinner the Warsaw Pact declaration expresses the East bloc's
determination ``for the conventional arms redutions talks in Vienna
to end with best possible results and in the shortest possible
time.''
   Ceausescu renewed what he termed the Soviet bloc's ``appeal to
NATO to give up its policy of nuclear deterrence'' and expressed
hope that new steps by the East bloc would draw a favorable response
from the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   Gorbachev said that, if Moscow's allies agreed, the Kremlin would
be ready to make further unilateral cuts in its European nuclear
arsenal once NATO agrees to talks on reducing short-range missiles.
   Earlier in the week while in France, Gorbachev assured East bloc
allies that each is free to find its own way to socialism.
   ``Each country and each party has its own specifics and can
continue its own individual road to socialist democracy and
progress,'' he said.
   Gorbachev added, however, that he hoped perestroika, the social
and economic reforms he has championed in the Soviet Union, would
serve as a model.
   Officials at the talks refused to comment on whether the
discussion involved friction between reform-oriented leaders in
Hungary, Poland, and the Soviet Union and their more orthodox
counterparts elsewhere in the bloc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
