<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Bombing     07-08 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Bombing,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Opens Hearings for North Korean Agent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeal hearing for a confessed North
Korea agent opened today with prosecutors demanding that she be
hanged for blowing up a South Korean airliner and killing 115 people
aboard.
   The prosecution asked the court to reject appeals of the agent,
Kim Hyon Hui, and uphold the lower court's verdict. ``Nothing can
extenuate her guilt,'' it said.
   She was sentenced to death April 25 by a lower court on charges
of violating national security and aviation laws.
   Several hundred security agents and police guarded the Seoul
Appellate Court today as the 27-year-old defendant was escorted into
the courthouse.
   As in earlier hearings, she admitted all charges and denounced
North Korean leader Kim Il Sung and his son and heir apparent, Kim
Jong Il. She said they ordered her to carry out the attack.
   After receiving the appeal, the appellate court adjourned for
later hearings.
   She has said she blew up the plane to disrupt last summer's
Olympic Games in Seoul. North Korea has denied involvement, claiming
South Korea engineered the attack to embarrass the communist north.
   The plane disappeared Nov. 29, 1987, as it approached the Burmese
coast on a flight from Baghdad, Iraq, to Seoul.
</TEXT>
