<DOCNO> AP890708-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Pamplona-RunningBulls     07-08 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pamplona-Running Bulls,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bull Gores Man in Face in Pamplona Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAMPLONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bull in the annual running of the bulls
today gored the face of one man, and police said 41 other people
were also injured during the race made famous by Ernest Hemingway.
   The weeklong San Fermin Festival opened Friday. Each day of the
event, a group of bulls chase revelers a half-mile through this
northern city's old quarter to the bull ring.
   Today, the run took two minutes, 37 seconds. An estimated 1,000
people scrambled ahead of the bulls.
   One of the bulls seriously injured Luis Sanchez Becerro, 33, of
Pamplona, by goring him in the right cheek, Navarre Hospital
spokesman Manuel Garcia said.
   Sanchez Becerro underwent surgery and remained in serious
condition, the doctor said.
   He also said 52-year-old Jose Loza Penafiel of Irun, Spain,
suffered a broken ankle when a bull trampled him.
   The rest of the injured were treated for bruises and scrapes at
Red Cross posts along the route, the Red Cross said.
   The festival is held annually in July to honor San Fermin,
Pamplona's patron saint. Hemingway's 1926 novel, ``The Sun Also
Rises,'' memorialized the race.
   Since the festival was first held in 1591, bulls have gored 52
people to death, 13 of them since 1924, according to city records.
</TEXT>
