<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0718EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     07-08 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zulu Leader Says United Black Action is Possible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival black factions that have
sometimes battled each other are working on a plan for unified
action to end apartheid, a Zulu leader said.
   ``I can well see future historians tracing a whole new political
era _ and in fact the final collapse of apartheid _ to this very
document and to the united action that it made possible,'' said Zulu
leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi late Friday.
   He made the comments in a statement released in advance of
today's meeting of his political organization, Inkatha.
   Buthelezi declined to provide details of the plan. He said it
would be discussed at a meeting of the African National Congress,
United Democratic Front and Inkatha. However, he gave no date.
   The plan was drafted last month at a meeting in Durban of
delegates from Inkatha, the front, and the Congress of South African
Trade Unions.
   Inkatha backers have been battling supporters of an alliance of
the two other groups for three years in Natal province in feuds and
revenge attacks that have killed about 2,000 people.
   In early June, the three groups opened peace talks, and violence
has decreased sharply since then.
   The outlawed ANC, the leading anti-apartheid group, is not part
of the talks. But its views are represented in them by delegates of
the front.
   The front, the union group and the ANC have in the past called
Buthelezi a collaborator with the apartheid system of racial
discrimination because of his position as chief minister of the Zulu
homeland and his opposition to tactics such as strikes, boycotts,
and other sanctions.
   He says these measures harm blacks more than the government.
Buthelezi, a member of the ANC in his youth, also believes the ANC's
bomb attacks and its claim to be the sole representative of South
Africa's blacks have hindered united black action.
   However, the Zulu leader said he now has high hopes for an
agreement. ``We could well be entering into an era in which black
politics is given a completely different face,'' he said.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 28 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
