<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0812EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     07-08 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fighting Continues In Lebanon, Despite Peace Initiative</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem gunmen battled in the
streets of west Beirut today, and Syrian and Christian troops traded
artillery fire across the city's Green Line. Six people were
reported killed and 28 wounded.
   The bloodshed undermined a new Arab League peace initative aimed
at ending the civil war's latest round of fighting, which began four
months ago.
   A Syrian-backed Moslem militia said Friday that it is seeking
surface-to-surface missiles to counter the Christians' reported
acquisition of Soviet-designed Frog-7 missiles from Iraq, Syria's
main Arab foe.
   With its 45-mile range, the Frog-7 could reach Syria's capital,
Damascus, if fired from the Christian-held sector of the central
mountains.
   The missile issue adds a new dimension to the 14-year-old civil
war by threatening to carry it beyond Lebanon's borders for the
first time.
   In today's clashes between the Syrian-backed Amal militia and the
pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, three people were killed and
12 wounded, police said.
   The Shiite factions have been fighting for leadership of
Lebanon's 1 million Shiites, the country's biggest sect. Their
battle broke out again eight days ago after a lull of several
months. Eight people have been killed and 28 wounded in the
inter-Shiite gunbattles since July 1.
   In the Syrian-Christian artillery duels across the
Moslem-Christian dividing line, three were killed and 16 wounded,
police said.
   Including the latest deaths, 408 people have been killed and
1,574 wounded since March 8 in fighting between Christian forces
loyal to army commander Gen. Michel Aoun and Syrian troops allied
with Moslem militiamen.
   Their latest battles began after Aoun's gunboats blockaded
illegal ports run by the Syrian-backed militias south of Beirut.
   Aoun, who also leads the Christian half of Lebanon's dual
government, has vowed to drive the Syrians from Lebanon. Syria keeps
about 40,000 troops here under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate.
   Despite repeated Arab League efforts to end the bloodshed,
fighting escalated sharply this week after Syria demanded that Aoun
remove the Frog-7 missiles he has reportedly obtained from Iraq.
   Amal leader Nabih Berri, Syria's main ally in Lebanon, threatened
Friday to acquire Frog-7s as well.
   Lakhdar Ibrahimi, the Arab League's assistant general secretary,
met with Aoun today seeking to ``work out a solution to the missile
issue,'' a source close to Aoun reported. The source spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   ``Ibrahimi is proposing that a special security committee be
created to search ships heading to our ports to make sure they
aren't bringing in weapons. Syria accepts this proposal,'' the
source said.
   However, the source said Aoun believes such a ban should apply
only to militias, not army forces he commands.
   Syrian gunboats have been patrolling off the coast of the
besieged Christian enclave for a week in an effort to tighten a
blockade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
