<FIRST>r i PM-Honecker     07-08 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honecker,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honecker Becomes Ill At Warsaw Pact Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Warsaw Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Erich Honecker, East Germany's leader, returned
home early from a Warsaw Pact summit in Bucharest, Romania, because
of an ``acute gallbladder ailment,'' the state-run news agency ADN
said today.
   The brief report gave no other details about the condition of
Honecker, who will be 77 on Aug. 25, and did not say if he had been
hospitalized upon his return to East Berlin. ADN said Honecker was
seen off early today by Romanian Communist Party leader Nicolae
Ceausescu.
   The official Romanian news agency Agerpres described Honecker's
illness as ``acute biliary trouble.'' Romanian officials and East
German journalists in Bucharest said he was suffering from a kidney
problem. Bile ducts carry digestive fluids from the liver or
gallbladder to the intestinal system.
   Honecker missed the signing of a Warsaw Pact agreement to seek a
nuclear-free Europe with significantly fewer soldiers and arms.
   The document was signed for East Germany by Premier Willi Stoph.
   Honecker became Communist Party leader in 1971 and assumed the
additional post of head of state in 1976.
   He has resisted carrying out the type of political and economic
reforms introduced in the Soviet Union by President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
