<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     07-08 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Southeast Asian Nations Favor Power Sharing In Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southeast Asian nations today
said Cambodia's guerrilla factions should form an interim government
and hold elections under U.N. supervision after Vietnamese troops
withdraw.
   The Association of Southeast Asian Nations, or ASEAN, said the
coalition government should include the Khmer Rouge and should
invite an international peacekeeping force to Cambodia until
elections are held.
   The weeklong ASEAN conference, which ended today, also called for
a forum on economic cooperation in the Pacific basin.
   The foreign ministers said an international conference on
Cambodia that begins July 30 in Paris should strive for a
U.N.-supervised agreement after Vietnam makes good on its promise to
withdraw its troops by Sept. 30 from the country it invaded in late
1978.
   The communique was issued by the foreign ministers of ASEAN,
which includes Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia, Indonesia, Brunei and
the Philippines, at the close of talks this week in this South
Pacific nation. Also attending the talks, which began Monday, were
United States, Canada, New Zealand and Japan.
   France's Deputy Foreign Minister Edwige Avice said prospects for
success have been brightened by China's announcement it will attend
the conference. China arms the guerrillas against Soviet-armed
Vietnam.
   A senior ASEAN diplomat, who spoke anonymously, said President
Francois Mitterrand of France asked Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev to exert influence on Vietnam to help ensure the success
of the conference.
   Cambodia said the ministers' wish to include the hard-line Khmer
Rouge in an interim government and introduce an international
peacekeeping force is against the spirit of peace talks in Jakarta
and agreements between Prince Norodom Sihanouk and Cambodian Prime
Minister Hun Sen.
   ``The Cambodian government...vehemently condemns attempts at
encouraging the Khmer Rouge to take part in any future government of
Cambodia,'' said the official Cambodian News Agency report seen in
Bangkok today.
   Sihanouk heads a three-party coalition which includes the Khmer
Rouge and is fighting the government in Phnom Penh. The Khmer Rouge
were responsible for the deaths of hundreds of thousands of
Cambodians during their 3{-year rule until they were ousted by the
Vietnamese invasion.
   At a concluding joint news conference today, Australian Foreign
Minister Gareth Evans rejected charges by the European Commission
that a new economic forum proposed by Canberra could turn into a
protectionist trading bloc.
   ``There is not a single country that is likely to join'' a forum
that is not committed to free trade, he said. He rejected the
European Commission's request to participate in the new forum.
   Evans said his government will invite 11 countries to an
exploratory meeting in Australia in November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
