<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 1003EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Women 1stLd-Writethru a0444 07-08 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Women, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,0790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Minister Tells Women to Stay Home, Out of Politics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 3rd graf `Uno told...' to UPDATE with
apology. Pickup 4th graf, `Major newspapers...'; Inserts 3 grafs after
7th, `Horinuchi also...' to ADD other quotes. Pickup 8th graf `Uno and
his...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new furor broke out in Japan today over reports
the agriculture minister for the governing political party declared
that women are ``useless in the world of politics'' and should stay
home.
   The comments Friday by Hisao Horinouchi in a campaign speech for
fellow Liberal Democrats in western Mie Prefecture were bound to
compound the problems of Prime Minister Sousuke Uno. His popularity
has already suffered, especially among women, as a result of claims
he paid a geisha to be his mistress.
   Uno told reporters today he would seek an explanation from
Horinouchi for the remarks.
   In a televised news conference this evening, Horinouchi said he
was sorry.
   ``I deeply apologize for having made remarks that have bothered
so many women,'' he said. ``I would like to retract them
completely.''
   Major newspapers reported today that Horinouchi said in his
speech, ``In the end, women's task is to stay home and take care of
their families.''
   Horinouchi also called the female head of the Japan Socialist
Party, Takako Doi, ``an idiot,'' according to the newspapers.
   ``There is no female congresswoman in the United States,'' he
added. In fact, at least 25 members of the U.S. House of
Representatives are women.
   Horinouchi also reportedly said, ``England's Prime Minister
(Margaret) Thatcher is special, and she has a husband and children.
But Socialist Party chairman Ms. Doi is single, and we must not
allow such a person who has never had a family to be a head of the
state.''
   ``Can women be useful in the political world?'' he was quoted as
asking. ``Even if they advance (into Parliament), they can't work as
legislators.'' Several women represent the Liberal Democratic Party
in Japan's Parliament.
   ``Women are useless in the world of politics,'' Horinouchi was
quoted as saying.
   ``In the end, women's task is to stay home and take care of their
families,'' he said.
   Uno and his Liberal Democratic Party have been reeling from the
geisha scandal and other embarrassments. After the former geisha
said Uno paid her more than $21,400 to be his mistress for four
months, Uno was reported to be considering resigning. He denied the
reports, however.
   The governing party has also been plagued by an
influence-peddling scandal in which government leaders and their
aides purchased stock at bargain prices. Uno's predecessor, Noboru
Takeshita, resigned in the midst of that scandal on June 2.
   The party has also taken a beating over an unpopular 3 percent
sales tax instituted April 1.
   Horinouchi was campaigning for an election on July 23 for the
upper house of the national parliament. Analysts say the Liberal
Democrats, the majority party in Parliament for 34 years, could lose
their majority.
   In Tokyo municipal elections Sunday, the governing party lost 20
seats, while the Japan Socialist Party gained 17. The Liberal
Democrats now hold 43 seats, and the Japan Socialist Party has 29.
   In that vote, 17 women were elected, up from seven in the
previous election in 1985. Analysts pointed to a high turnout among
woman voters.
   Chief Cabinet Secretary Masajuro Shiokawa defended Horinouchi to
reporters today, saying, ``He did not mean to look down upon
women,'' according to the Kyodo news agency.
   But party Secretary General Ryutaro Hashimoto told a news
conference the reported remarks were ``a slander to LDP female
candidates,'' Kyodo said. He added that Horinouchi should ``take
back his remarks if he really meant what he said,'' it reported.
   Horinouchi's remarks, published on the front pages today of the
Mainichi Shimbun and the Yomiuri Shimbun, two of the country's major
dailies, angered many women.
   One who answered the phone at the party's own election committee
told The Associated Press that Horinouchi's remarks were
``unpleasant and ridiculous.''
   ``Women are finally getting interested in and trying to
participate in politics,'' said the official, who spoke on condition
of anonymity. ``So I resent any statement that interferes with the
trend.''
   Ms. Doi, on a campaign trip to Osaka, told Kyodo today that
Horinouchi's remarks only show how much his party is suffering.
   ``He still doesn't seem to realize that LDP politics are so
rotten women can't keep quiet any more,'' Kyodo quoted Ms. Doi as
saying.
   She said his remarks may further anger female voters over the
governing party, the agency said.
</TEXT>
