<FIRST>r i PM-Bush-EasternEurope     07-08 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Eastern Europe,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Pledges U.S. Support For Change In Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said the United States
stands ready to support political and economic change in Eastern
Europe but is not going to tell the region how to go about it,
Hungarian news media reported today.
   ``It is not an American president's role to say to those in
another country, `You have to have your system this way, matching
our system, or else we can't do business with you,''' he was quoted
as saying.
   His comments came in a recent interview with Hungarian
journalists in Washington. Excerpts were released today by
government-run media in Budapest.
   Bush said changes taking place in Poland and Hungary will make it
``much easier for the United States to be a full partner in economic
development and economic reform,'' according to MTI, Hungary's
state-run news agency.
   Bush arrives in Poland on Sunday and travels to Budapest on
Tuesday.
   Bush was quoted as saying the visits are designed to ``salute''
political and economic reforms under way in Poland and Hungary.
   Asked if Hungary could expect increased economic aid, Bush said:
   ``I wish that I was going to be in a free-fall in terms of the
funds we could bring to bear on the problem. We aren't. But we will
try to have some ideas and some funds that can be helpful in some
way to Hungary.''
   He added: ``I'm going to be sure that your leaders know that
there are certain confines within which I have to operate.''
   He said members of Congress will ``want to be sure that economic
performance matches our expectations if we're going to give money or
other countries are going to give money.''
   But Bush pledged that to the ``degree change can accommodate
privatization or more market for us or more openness towards the
West, then we can do more.''
   Bush said economic aid to Poland and Hungary would be high on the
agenda when leaders of the world's most industrialized nations meet
in Paris for a summit next week.
   The president was quoted as saying that while there are
``exciting changes'' going on in Poland and Hungary, the United
States should not meddle in the domestic affairs of Warsaw Pact
nations. ``I think a country like the United States ought not to
over-promise, ought not to over-exhort for others to be like us and
thus make problems worse for the people.''
   Hungary's ruling Communist Party and opposition groups have
agreed to hold multiparty elections by next summer and the country
has embarked on market-orientated economic reforms, including more
cooperation with the West.
   But the country still suffers from a staggering foreign debt,
high inflation and erratic consumer supplies.
   Poland recently legalized Solidarity and held its freest
elections in more than 40 years. Solidarity-backed candidates won a
major role in the government.
</TEXT>
