<HEAD>Day-Care Protest Disrupts Ceremony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters hurling plastic baby bottles on Saturday
burst into a square where U.S. Ambassador Walter Curley was speaking
and demanded more city funding for day-care centers.
   The protest disrupted a ceremony inaugurating the renovated
square honoring the United States.
   About 100 demonstrators chanted ``Money for day care, not for the
bicentennial!'' France is celebrating the 200th anniversary of its
revolution.
   The protesters carried leaflets calling for a ``Declaration of
the Rights of Children to Day Care.'' Blocked by lines of police
officers, they chanted slogans while the U.S. and French national
anthems were played at the end of the ceremony.
   Besides Curley, Paris Mayor Jacques Chirac also spoke at the
inauguration of the renovated park in the Place des Etats-Unis, in a
prosperous neighborhood just south of the Arc de Triomphe.
