<FIRST>r a AM-WallaceBrother     07-08 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wallace Brother,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gerald Wallace, Former Governor's Brother, Indicted For $165,000
Tax Evasion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILLIP RAWLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerald Wallace, the younger brother of
former Gov. George C. Wallace, will surrender to U.S. marshals next
week on charges of failing to pay income taxes on more than
$165,000, a federal prosecutor said.
   U.S. Attorney Jim Wilson said Friday the charges involve Gerald
Wallace's tax returns for 1984 and 1985 _ years when George Wallace
was serving as governor _ but they do not concern any work the
68-year-old Montgomery attorney was doing concerning state
government.
   Wilson described the fees as ``a private type thing'' paid by
individuals in the Mobile area, but he declined to elaborate.
   Gerald Wallace was a frequently at the Capitol during his
brother's four terms, but Wilson said the charges should not cast a
shadow on George Wallace's administrations, only on ``the named
defendant.''
   Telephone calls to Gerald Wallace's Montgomery law office and
home went unanswered Friday and again Saturday morning.
   Wilson said the two-count indictment for filing false income tax
returns was handed down by a federal grand jury in Montgomery late
Thursday afternoon. If convicted, Wallace could be sentenced to a
maximum of three years in prison and fined $100,000 on each count.
In addition, he could be required to pay back taxes and interest,
Wilson said.
   Wilson said the case began developing more than two years ago
based on information supplied by the state Department of Revenue.
The indictment against Wallace said he reported $255,943 in income
in 1984 and failed to report $30,195. In 1985, he reported $88,582
in income but failed to report about $135,000, the indictment
alleged.
</TEXT>
