<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     07-08 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Arabs Dead, Two Shot By Palestinians, One By Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian assailants fatally shot two Arabs
suspected of collaborating with Israeli authorities, and soldiers
shot and killed a third Arab, news reports said today.
   The deaths raised to 549 the number of Palestinians killed in the
19-month uprising against Israeli rule. At least 33 Israelis have
also been slain.
   Fifteen Palestinians were reported injured in clashes with
soldiers that occurred Friday night and today in at least six towns
and refugee camps in the occupied territories, Arab reports said.
   The army confirmed one Arab fatality and said it was
investigating the circumstances. Other casualty reports were being
checked, it said.
   Jewish militants continued stoning attacks on Arab cars, in
apparent retaliation for a bus crash caused by a Palestinian
passenger on Thursday, in which 14 people were killed and 27 injured.
   Protesters shouting ``Death to the Arabs!'' gathered in
Jerusalem's Shmuel Hanavi Quarter today and stoned Palestinian
motorists, smashing the window of at least one vehicle, police said.
One suspect was detained.
   On Friday night a 27-year-old Palestinian man was seriously
injured by a rock hurled at his car in Jerusalem's Talpiot quarter,
Arab reports said.
   Also today, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said his Cabinet would
consider new measures to confront the uprising in response to the
bus crash, which was the worst assault on an Israeli target since
the rebellion began Dec. 8, 1987.
   One possibility, Shamir said on Israel radio, was imposing a
death penalty on terrorists convicted of murder.
   Shamir gave no details about other restrictions being considered.
   Israeli law allows capital punishment as a sentence for murder,
but judges have refrained from giving this penalty to Arabs, fearing
possible retaliation against Israeli prisoners held in Arab
countries.
   One of the Palestinians slain today was Mustafa Abed el Saed, 42,
who was shot in the head and neck in Gaza City's Sejaiyeh Quarter as
he rode his motorcycle to work in Gaza City, Arab reports said.
   The reports said that El Saed was killed on suspicion of
providing information to the Israeli authorities.
   Palestinians also reportedly killed Ismail Hussein Al Ghoush, 55,
of Yatta in the West Bank. Al Ghoush was shot in the abdomen with a
pistol by masked men who broke into his home Friday night, Arab
reports said.
   An army spokesman confirmed the fatality in Yatta, calling it the
result ``of a clash between Arabs,'' and saying the shooting was
under investigation.
   In Gaza, soldiers opened fire on stone-throwing demonstrators in
a marketplace in Rafah, killing Ziad Zaki Abu Olwan, 20. Eight of
the 15 Palestinians wounded today were injured in the Rafah
confrontation.
</TEXT>
