<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 1129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     07-08 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factional Strife Rocks Beirut; Six Reported Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>By MOHAMMED SALAM</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias battled in
the streets of west Beirut on Saturday, while Syrian and Christian
gunners dueled with howitzers across the city's dividing Green Line.
   By police count, six people were killed and 28 wounded in the
separate fighting.
   A police spokesman said three people were killed and 12 wounded
in overnight clashes between the Syrian-backed mainstream Shiite
Amal militia and the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   The two factions are vying for dominance of the 1.2 million
Shiites, the largest sect in Lebanon.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named in line with police rules,
said the fighting with automatic rifles and rocket-propelled
grenades damaged dozens of cars and started fires in several
apartments.
   The intermittent clashes erupted anew July 1, with the fighting
over the last two days starting in the seaside Ouzai district and
spreading to nearby Haret Hreik.
   Helmeted Syrian troops responsible for security in west Beirut
patrolled the two districts in an effort to disengage the
combatants, the police spokesman said.
   ``The situation is calm, but very tense. Gunmen remain in
entrances to buildings,'' he said.
   Another three people died and 16 were wounded in artillery duels
between Syrian and Christian gunners, police said.
   This brought the overall toll to 408 people killed and 1,574
wounded in the confrontation, which began in March after the army
commander, Gen. Michel Aoun, closed illegal militia-run ports that
were sapping the nation of tax revenues.
   Syria and its allied militias retaliated by bombarding the
Christian enclave, home to about 1 million people.
   The dispute was complicated Friday by threats from Nabih Berri,
head of the Shiite Amal militia, to obtain medium-range missiles to
counter Soviet-designed Frog-7 missiles believed delivered to the
Christians from Iraq.
   The missiles have a range of 43 miles, meaning they could hit the
Syrian capital, Damascus, from the 310-square-mile Christian enclave
northeast of Beirut.
   Berri, Syria's closest ally in Lebanon, threatened to deploy
Frog-7s in Moslem areas.
   Lakhdar Ibrahimi, the assistant secretary general of the Arab
League, met with Aoun on Saturday in an effort to resolve the issue.
It was his third meeting with Aoun in as many days.
   A source close to Aoun, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Ibrahimi is proposing that a special security committee be created
to search ships heading to ports to ensure they are not carrying
weapons.
   ``Syria accepts this proposal,'' the source said.
   He said Aoun ``accepts that a ban on the import of weapons be
imposed on all militias in Lebanon. But he strongly rejects the
imposing of such measures on the Lebanese army, because the army
cannot be treated as a militia,'' the source added.
   ``Whether an army imports weapons or not is a decision for its
command and its national authorities to take. This is a practice of
sovereignty that the general will not give up,'' he said.
   After his 90-minute discussion with Aoun, Ibrahimi crossed to
west Beirut and held a meeting with 10 Moslem parliament deputies.
   He described his talks as ``good and positive,'' but refused to
disclose details.
   Ibrahimi was sent by the leaders of Morocco, Saudi Arabia and
Algeria, who were assigned by an Arab summit in May to find a
settlement to Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
</TEXT>
