<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Britain     07-08 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Britain,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tehran Paper Warns of Violence If Britain Rejets Moslem Demands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Tehran newspaper said Saturday that
Britain's Moslems might resort to violence if the British government
does not punish author Salman Rushdie, the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
   ``The Moslems in Britain might have to consider ways that perhaps
might not sit well with the desire for coexistence,'' the agency
quoted the English-language daily Tehran Times as saying in an
editorial.
   ``If and when such developments shape up, it will be only out of
ignorance that one could blame the Moslem community for the violence
that might occur,'' the paper added.
   The warning came two days after a bomb blast damaged a London
bookshop. British authorities said the bomb was part of Moslems'
campaign against Rushdie's latest novel, ``The Satanic Verses,''
which some consider insulting to Islam.
   Moslems have demanded the amendment of Britain's blasphemy law so
that legal action can be taken against Rushdie.
   The Indian-born author, who is a naturalized British citizen, has
been in hiding since Feb. 14 when the late Iranian spiritual leader,
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, issued an edict urging Moslems to kill
him.
   Two Iranian Moslem clergymen backed Khomeini by offering a total
of $5.2 million for Rushdie's death.
   Moslems in Britain have staged several public demonstrations
since then demanding the banning of the novel and Rushdie's
punishment.
   The issue led Iran to break diplomatic relations with London in
March.
   The Tehran Times said that it was predictable that given ``the
racist orientation'' of the Cabinet of British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher, ``no justice would be done to the Moslem
minority.''
</TEXT>
