<SECOND>AM-Soccer Violence, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0481,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazilian Players Detained After Attacking Referee</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout to UPDATE with report players charged with assault,
details from court hearing. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Brazilian soccer players were
charged with assault Saturday after allegedly kicking a referee
during a match, the national news agency TT reported.
   The incident occured Friday night during a Stockholm Soccer Cup
semifinal between the Botafogo team from Brazil and Spanga IS, a
local team.
   Stig Sterneberg, a police duty officer, said the Swedish referee,
Kaari Grundstrom, was attacked when he ordered a Brazilian player
off the field in a match that had been ``messy'' from the start.
   ``A Botafogo coach rushed onto the field. At the same time, the
referee was kicked to the ground by one player and in the head by
another,'' he said.
   The referee suffered minor injuries and briefly lost
consciousness. He was able to go home after seeing a doctor,
Sterneberg said.
   One player, 33, said during court proceedings that he had been
ordered off the field earlier in the match, and he denied ever going
near Grundstrom, the national news agency TT said.
   The other player, 26, admitted he pushed Grundstrom but couldn't
remember beating him, TT said. The player had been disqualified from
the tournament for foul play.
   None of the players was identified.
   Police detained four members of Botafogo, but only two were in
police custody. One was released and another was banned from leaving
Stockholm and ordered to report regularly to the police.
   The team was participating in a tournament involving about 5,000
players from 15 countries. The 14 other Brazilian teams
participating apologized to the board of judges for Botafogo's
behavior, TT said.
