<FIRST>r a AM-Extradition-Reax     07-08 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Extradition-Reax,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Blasts Ruling Protecting Diplomat's Son</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEDFORD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international court's ruling against
extradition of a double-murder suspect prompted ``outrage'' from
officials here, and a vow that capital charges won't be dropped
despite the ruling that the death penalty violates human rights.
   Bedford Commonwealth's Attorney James Updike said Friday he will
ask the U.S. State Department to pressure British officials to
ignore the ruling and extradite Jens Soering, a West German
diplomat's son.
   Updike called the ruling outrageous and said he it believed it
was based on politics and diplomacy rather than logic.
   Soering, 22, is accused of stabbing and slitting the throats of
Derek and Nancy Haysom in their Bedford County home in March 1985.
The retired steel executive and his wife were the parents of
Soering's girlfriend at the time, Elizabeth Haysom. She pleaded
guilty to helping plan the slayings and is serving a 90-year prison
sentence in Virginia. Soering was arrested in Britain.
   The European Court of Human Rights ruled Friday that extraditing
Soering would violate his human rights because he faces the death
penalty.
   Rulings by the court, a branch of the 23-nation Council of
Europe, are not binding to the 23 nations but are rarely ignored.
   Soering, who is in a London prison, has been fighting extradition
to the United States since May 1986. West Germany has also requested
his extradition, seeking to let him stand trial there under a law
that allows West Germans accused of crimes in other countries to be
tried in their homeland. He would face a maximum sentence of 10 to
15 years if tried in West Germany.
   Soering boasted in a letter to Ms. Haysom a few months after
their arrest in London that diplomatic steps would block his
extradition to Bedford County. She had returned to the United States
voluntarily.
   ``Those yokels don't know what's coming down,'' Soering had
written in a letter, which became public during Ms. Haysom's legal
proceedings. He predicted he would go to West Germany, ``and then
I'll be out in a surprisingly short time.''
   Updike was incensed by that prospect Friday.
   ``This individual brutally murdered two human beings,'' Updike
said during a news conference at the Bedford County Courthouse.
``They may very well turn him loose.''
   Soering's attorney said the European Court's decision ``means
that the tragedy of four years ago will not be compounded by another
homicide.''
   ``For the U.S., it means that a significant segment of the
world's population now rejects the U.S. death penalty system,''
Richard Neaton said in a statement released from his office in
Detroit, where Soering's father was stationed.
   Updike said the decision ``is founded in politics and diplomacy.
It is without question, outrageous.''
   The international court allowed extradition in two previous death
penalty cases, he said, and the only difference in this case was
that the defendant had diplomatic and political connections.
   Updike also challenged the court's argument that Soering, if
found guilty, would face years on death row _ punishment that would
breach his rights under the European Human Rights Convention.
   ``If there is a delay in the appellate process it occurs at his
request,'' Updike said.
   Updike maintained he would not compromise by dropping the capital
murder charge and agreeing to try Soering on lesser charges of
first-degree murder.
   ``I do not negotiate with murderers,'' he said. ``I'm not going
to negotiate with him or anyone else on his behalf. ... Murder is
not a matter of diplomacy.''
   Soering's father, Klaus Soering, is vice consul at the West
German consulate in Detroit. The German government argued on behalf
of his son before the European court.
   The Council of Europe, the oldest organization striving for
European unity, was founded in 1949 and is separate from the
12-nation European Economic Community.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
