<FIRST>r w AM-Glenn-SovietSpace     07-08 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Glenn-Soviet Space,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Calls for Go-Slow Approach on Space Cooperation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John Glenn, the first American to orbit
the Earth, says he does not favor a high level of cooperation with
the Soviet Union in space because the United States would have to
reveal a lot of advanced technology.
   ``I don't want to see the focal point of the world's attention on
scientific greatness going to the Soviet Union and the kids of the
world aspiring to go to Patrice Lumumba University in Moscow instead
of Ohio State or Cal Tech or MIT,'' the Ohio Democrat said in a
television interview taped for broadcast on Sunday.
   ``I don't want to see us transfer a lot of technology over there
and help that whole program out,'' Glenn said on the program ``John
McLaughlin's One on One.''
   He said the United States and the Soviet Union have had
cooperative programs for a long time _ the 1975 Apollo-Soyuz linkup
in space was an example _ but said some agreements were not carried
out by the Soviets.
   Glenn said he would not object to having the Soviets taking part
in the space station program by buying a module as the European
Space Agency and the Japanese are doing.
   ``If we start cooperation like that, OK,'' Glenn said. ``But as
far as having another Apollo-Soyuz type thing, I'd sort of question
that one.''
</TEXT>
