<FIRST>u a PM-Hostages-Shooting 2ndLd-Writethru a0470 07-08 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages-Shooting, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0470,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Employee Captured After Shooting Two</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs the last 3 grafs with 3 grafs to update with names of victims
and tighten.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTELL, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fired Coca-Cola driver who killed two of
his superiors and holed up in the company's office for seven hours
emerged this morning firing his guns and was fatally shot by police,
authorities said.
   John Wallace, 45, seized and released a hostage after shooting
the two men, who allegedly had fired him earlier Friday night, then
blockaded himself in the Coca-Cola West Metro Sales Center, said
Cobb County Police Chief Culver Johnson.
   He negotiated with police in this northern Atlanta suburb for
most of the night.
   Around 5 a.m. police fired tear gas into the building, a
distribution and sales office, and Wallace agreed to come out
without his guns, Johnson said.
   Instead, Wallace emerged with two guns and fired at police, he
said.
   ``They had no choice but to return the fire,'' Johnson said.
   Wallace was taken to Cobb General Hospital, where nursing
supervisor Linda Cole later said Wallace had died.
   Johnson said Wallace came to work at the plant near the Six Flags
Over Georgia amusement park around 10 p.m. and was told of his
dismissal. The reason for his firing was not immediately known.
   Witnesses told police that Wallace then went to clean out his
locker but returned with a handgun and fired on a gathering of
workers, shooting two of them.
   A caller who identified himself as Wallace telephoned WSB-TV in
Atlanta and told reporters he had shot two men. Police said
officials at the station acted as negotiators by telephone until
police took over.
   David Kenney, an associate producer at WSB, said the caller
described having worked 23 years for the company and said he shot
the plant manager who fired him and his supervisor.
   The victims were removed from the building within about an hour
of the shooting. One died at the scene and the other died later at a
hospital.
   Cobb County police identified the slain supervisors as Maurice
McCluskey of Decatur and Al Parsons. Their ages and Parsons' address
were not immediately available, said Ben Brannon, emergency operator
at the police department.
   Police said two other employees who were in the building managed
to escape.
</TEXT>
