<FIRST>u i PM-Mandela 2ndLd-Writethru a0508 07-08 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mandela, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0508,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Botha Holds Secret Meeting With Mandela</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 5th pvs, ``The minister...'' to ADD that
government announced meeting after word leaked out. Pickup 6th, ``Mandela,
who...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha invited
Nelson Mandela, the imprisoned African National Congress leader, to
his official residence this week for a conversation, the government
announced today.
   It was the first time the two are known to have met and increased
speculation that Botha may free Mandela before leaving office in the
fall.
   Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee said Mandela, who is serving a
life prison term at the Victor Verster prison farm north of Cape
Town, paid a ``courtesy visit'' Wednesday to Tuynhuys, Botha's
official residence in the city center.
   Coetsee said no policy matters were debated and no negotiations
were conducted but that the two men ``availed themselves of the
opportunity to confirm their support for peaceful development in
South Africa.''
   The minister said the 45-minute conversation took place in a
``pleaseant spirt'' but the possibility of ``further steps or
meetings was not discussed during the occasion.'' Coetsee said he
was present during the visit.
   Normally, such a major announcement would not have been made on a
Saturday night. But a reporter for the independent South African
Press Association heard about the visit and called a spokesman for
Coetsee, who confirmed it.
   The announcement was carried by the news agency and subsequently
read on government-run television. Spokesmen for the justice
minister would not say why the meeting had been kept secret.
   Mandela, who will be 71 years old on July 18, has been in prison
since 1962. He was sentenced to life in prison in 1964 after being
convicted of sabotage and plotting to overthrow of the government.
   He is the nation's most respected black leader, and other leaders
of the black majority have refused to negotiate with the government
until he is freed.
   Botha, 73, is to retire after the September parliamentary
elections, and there has been widespread speculation he may free
Mandela before stepping down.
   In the past, Botha refused to consider freeing the ANC leader
unless he renounced violence, which Mandela refused to do unless the
government halted violence against blacks. However, during the past
year, Botha has dropped the renunciation requirement and said he
hopes it will be possible to free Mandela.
   The ANC is a primarily black guerrilla group fighting the
nation's white-led government. The group, based in Lusaka, Zambia,
is banned in South Africa.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 28 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs.
   The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate
districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
