<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-US     07-08 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-US,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army General Says U.S. Should Use Military Option In Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should consider a
military solution to remove Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega from power
in Panama, according to a commanding general in the U.S. Army's
Southern Command.
   ``I've been thinking more and more that the United States should
impose a military solution that would give this country an
opportunity to have a government that isn't criminal,'' Brig. Gen.
Marc A. Cisneros said in an interview.
   ``This is my personal opinion,'' Cisneros emphasized in the
interview Friday. ``This is a political decision I do not make. Any
U.S. military action is decided by the president.''
   Cisneros' U.S. Army South is part of the U.S. Southern Command
and includes Army forces charged with the defense of the Panama
Canal under the Torrijos-Carter Treaties of 1977.
   Cisneros was the Southern Command's chief of operations until two
weeks ago. In that job, he had frequent contact with officers of the
Panamanian Defense Forces.
   ``Noriega sees me as a definite threat,'' he said. ``Before, I
used to have some serious and frank discussions with some of the
officers and would tell them how Noriega was using them. I would
tell them `You are next.'''
   Cisneros often criticizes Noriega and the Defense Forces and he
is in turn attacked by the government media, which claim he has
betrayed his Mexican-American ancestry by becoming an Army general
and leading U.S. forces in Panama.
   The removal of the Panamanian general, Cisneros said, ``would
ensure democracy for this country. From the beginning I always
thought that Panamanians should do it, but if they do not, if they
do not have the desire, then they deserve him.''
   ``If we acted militarily,'' Cisneros said, ``from what we know
the majority of the Defense Forces will not fight.''
   ``But we would act only if there is a threat to U.S. interests,''
he said.
   ``Time is on our side,'' Cisneros said. ``Things will continue to
deteriorate.''
   The American general said he saw little chance of an internal
coup by disenchanted Panamanian officers.
   ``Some officers want us to act militarily, but those are the same
that probably tell Noriega they are loyal to him. They know their
fate depends on Noriega's survival. I do not see anyone there with
moral courage,'' he said.
   The United States has been trying to oust Noriega since a Miami
court last year indicted him on drug trafficking charges.
   On May 7, Noriega annulled presidential elections. International
observers say a slate led by the opposition's Guillermo Endara beat
Noriega's candidate, Carlos Duque, by at least a 3-1 margin.
   Noriega claims the U.S. government financed the opposition's
campaign and intervened to distort the results.
   Noriega also charges that the United States wants to renege on
the Panama Canal treaties that specify U.S. forces must leave Panama
on the last day of the year 1999, when Panama takes over total
administration of the canal.
   Under the treaties, the United States maintains nearly 12,000
soldiers in military bases here.
</TEXT>
