<DOCNO> AP890708-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 1325EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     07-08 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Kills 20 Guerrillas In Jungle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army killed 20 Shining Path guerrillas in
two raids in the coca-growing jungle region northeast of the
capital, the government said Saturday.
   One soldier was wounded in the operation, carried out Thursday
with ground troops and helicopters in the state of Huanuco,
according to the report.
   The state of Huanuco encompasses most of the Upper Huallaga
Valley, the world's richest coca-growing region. The government has
said the Shining Path operates in league with drug traffickers in
the area, allowing them to move their products in exchange for cash.
   In the first rebel encounter, an army patrol surprised a camp of
70 guerrillas near La Morada, 185 miles northeast of Lima, killing
15 rebels.
   The army, with helicopter support, then attacked another camp in
the area, killing five rebels, officials said.
   President Alan Garcia has said the threat of ``radical and
violent communism'' is greater in Peru than anywhere else in Latin
America.
   The Shining Path, a Mao-inspired group started by a Marxist
university professor in the early 1970s, took up arms against Peru's
elected government in 1980.
   The insurgency began in the highland state of Ayacucho, 235 miles
southeast of Lima, but has spread through most of the highlands and
northern jungle regions.
   The government has said nearly 15,000 people have died in the
9-year-old uprising, including soldiers, police, guerrillas and
government officials. Most of the dead, however, have been peasants
killed in the cross fire between the army and the rebels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890708-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 1326EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     07-08 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big-screen movie magic returned to this
small Indiana town for the first time in six years, sending
couch-potato residents to the box office in droves.
   ``Portland's been dead for so long, now it's starting to come
alive,'' said Betty Miller, clerk-treaurer of the town 45 miles
south of Fort Wayne.
   Michael Volpe, an engineer, and Charles H. Miller, a dentist,
were tired of driving to Fort Wayne or 30 miles southwest to Muncie
whenever they wanted to see a movie.
   And for Volpe, who keeps a log of more than 2,500 movies he's
seen, that has meant several trips a week.
   ``It's not unusual for me and my lady to go up to Fort Wayne or
Muncie and see at least two movies and sometimes three in an
afternoon,'' he said.
   So the men teamed up to bring the big-screen back to 7,000
residents who have gone without a theater since July 1983. That's
when Portland's only indoor theater was destroyed by a fire that
killed its live-in projectionist.
   Shortly before that, a fire closed down Portland's drive-in
theater.
   The new movie house, the art-deco Ritz, is housed in a
100-year-old converted furniture store with 14 apartments on the top
floor. The theater had its grand opening Friday night with a
$10-per-person benefit featuring a 1936 film of Portland's
centennial. More than 200 tickets were sold in advance.
   But the weekend bill, which included a Friday afternoon showing,
offered jazzier fare, including the films ``Lethal Weapon 2'' and
``K-9.''
   Mitch Harter, 14, was excited at the prospect of a day at the
Ritz.
   ``There's not much to do in town for young people except to
cruise and get in trouble,'' said the boy, who rode his bicycle up
and down Meridian Street waiting to attend the afternoon show.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four flat tires in one day didn't keep a
bright red 1924 Bentley from roaring across the finish line with
just seconds to spare in a race from Virginia to Disneyland.
   Dick Burdick drove the classic car from coast to coast to take
first place and $50,000 Friday in the Interstate Batteries Great
American Race.
   The Rosanky, Texas, resident had finished second in the 12-day,
3,500-mile road rally the previous two years.
   ``We finally broke the spell and did it,'' said Burdick, who has
participated in the antique car race for seven consecutive years.
   ``The most frustrating time was the day with all the flat
tires,'' he said. ``It's a rally and you can't rally if you don't
have four wheels under you.''
   The flat tires were between Santa Fe, N.M., and Phoenix.
   Burdick and his navigator, Wayne Bell of Lake Oswego, Ore.,
nudged out Alan Travis, who was last year's winner.
   Travis, from Phoenix, and his navigator, Wayne Stanfield of
Tustin, Calif., drove a 1916 Egge Machine Co. Mitchell Roadster.
   In all, the race featured 113 cars made before World War II. It
began in Norfolk, Va., on June 26.
   The competition, which usually runs from West to East, was a
little tougher this year because it started in the East and headed
West, leaving the desert crossing for the final grueling days.
   In previous years, the desert was the first leg of the journey
``and once you get across the Great Divide, it's all downhill from
there,'' said Sam Cole, one of the organizers of Greatrace, Ltd.
</TEXT>
