<DOCNO> AP890708-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 1410EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-TheStones'Phones Bjt   07-08 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-The Stones' Phones, Bjt,0741</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Three Generations, `Stone' Has Meant `Phone' in Magazine, Ark.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAGAZINE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In what once was her mother's living room,
Doris Stone Jones supervises the business office of the Magazine
Telephone Co., where customers using the 765 lines _ the town has
799 residents _ are greeted by their first names.
   Three generations of Stones have kept the telephone lines humming
in this western Arkansas community for half a century.
   Mrs. Jones remembers how, as a child, she could hear operators at
the parlor switchboard and neighborly chatter on party lines.
   Her brother, Hank Stone, monitors the constantly clicking
switches in the narrow red-brick technical building next door, while
his sons _ Denny, Chris and Vic _ take care of outside wiring.
   Chris' wife, Cheryl, punches billing information into the
company's brand-new, and only, computer terminal.
   The Magazine Telephone Co. is listed by the Public Service
Commission as the second-smallest of the state's 30 telephone
companies.
   ``In a small town, you get a lot of personal service,'' said Mrs.
Jones, 61, whose parents, Henry and Anna Stone, bought the company
in August 1939. ``Our family is so telephone-oriented, our family
reunion was a telephone convention in Oklahoma City.''
   In 1939, the company had 10 customers, two pay phones and
hay-baling wire for emergency repairs. During World War II, students
worked part time as operators; a full-time vacation relief operator
earned a dime an hour.
   On election nights, Anna Stone, now retired, stayed up late to
relay returns to the county seat at Paris, 15 miles away.
   In the 1950s, lines were run to nearby Waveland, Blue Mountain
and Sugar Grove, and the company went to dial service. Twenty-two
customers once crowded a single party line to Waveland. By 1970, the
company had two exchanges _ 947 and 969.
   Mrs. Jones said technical advances haven't hampered the
neighborly nature of the operation, where basic service costs $8.31
a month. The family understood when one customer, short on cash,
dropped her wedding ring into the night depository slot. The ring
was returned, Mrs. Jones said.
   The business office, replete with color portraits of 10
grandchildren, offers telephone directories published by the Contel
phone company, where Hank Stone works during the day as a senior
technician.
   Magazine's listings are included in the Contel book because it's
too expensive to publish a local directory, Mrs. Jones said. The
Stones are frugal in other ways, too, including the avoidance of
such modern business practices as taking out loans.
   ``We don't borrow,'' she said. ``Everything you see is ours.''
   Hank's sons, who all began full-time at the job at the age of 18
or so, took a lunch break at the business office the other day,
after an early start to repair lines knocked out by storms during
the night.
   ``I was out till 11:30 getting the phone back up at the ranger
station in Waveland,'' said Chris, 29.
   Added Denny, 33, ``One came to my house last night and left a
message about service being out. They're back up now.''
   ``It's a living. It's a job,'' said Vic, 31. ``We ain't getting
rich, but we live comfortable.''
   All three sons learned their work from their dad, helping out
during summer vacations before they began full time. The education
came in handy when a chicken feed truck driver forgot to lower his
boom and tore down a mile of cable on a Fourth of July, recalled
Chris.
   ``Yep, we work holidays if we need to,'' he said. ``And we did
get to shoot fireworks later that night.''
   Don Dickens, chief of the Magazine volunteer fire department,
praises the company's cooperation.
   ``When there's a fire, you dial 8400 and it rings 20 different
telephones at 20 different firemen's houses. And everybody just
picks up the phone and finds out the location,'' Dickens said.
``It's like a conference call, and it works great.''
   The firemen's phones also are rigged with a button that sets off
a public siren, Dickens said.
   ``Now that's telephone service,'' he said.
   Postmaster Phyllis Webster agrees.
   ``It's small, yes, but I don't have any complaints about the
telephone company,'' she said. ``I'm comfortable with it, and it
suits the way we live here just really well.''
</TEXT>
