<FIRST>r i AM-France-Bicentennial     07-08 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Bicentennial,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Bands, Twirlers Salute French Revolution</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American marching bands and majorettes strutted
their stuff Saturday in central Paris in a lively U.S. salute to the
200th anniversary of the French Revolution.
   Several thousand people crowded around City Hall and the
surrounding side streets to catch a glimpse of the plumed hats,
fluttering flags and flying batons of the 600 performers.
   The daylong U.S. homage to the bicentennial kicks off a week of
celebrations, culminating Friday on Bastille Day, the 200th
anniversary of the storming of the Bastille prison.
   President Bush will be among about 30 world leaders in town for
the parades and fireworks, followed by the annual economic summit of
the world's seven largest industrial democracies.
   The Montana Centennial Band, in white cowboy hats and blue jeans,
led the short parade to cheers from crowds along the avenue.
   The Virginia Military Institute's band, in plumed hats and
gray-and-white uniforms, was next down the Avenue Victoria, followed
by the Marching Panthers of James B. Dudley High School in
Greensboro, N.C., the North Springs (Ga.) High School band and the
Lawrence Central (Ind.) High School band, led by flagbearers waving
the American, French and Indiana colors.
   Marching bands are a rarity in France and are considered
quintessentially American, but the most exotic spectacle came last,
with the 28 members of the Touch of Kyle Twirling Club of Kalamazoo,
Mich., spinning their batons, flags and pink rifles.
   The event's announcer, addressing the crowd over speakers mounted
at City Hall, described baton-twirling as ``this very American art,
which consists of marching in time to the music, spinning and
tossing the little batons while executing all sorts of arabesques.''
   The young Americans are participating in a variety of events
marking the bicentennial around France.
   ``I was really proud of our school that we got chosen,'' said
Andrea Varrone, a clarinet player in the North Springs band. ``We've
been touring and shopping. It's been a lot of fun.''
   The Virginia Military Institute band, from Lexington, Va., played
earlier in the day at the inauguration of a renovated square
honoring the United States.
   It is to lead a civic parade in the city of Vendome, 100 miles
southwest of Paris, commemorating ties between Virginia and France.
The band members plan to tour the Ecole Polytechnique, the historic
French military engineering academy that served as the model for the
Virginia Military Institute, which celebrates its 150th anniversary
this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890708-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-NAACP Bjt   07-08 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NAACP, Bjt,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>20,000 Gather to Debate, Regain Momentum in Rights Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From San Francisco and Dallas, from small towns in
Mississippi and Michigan, about 20,000 NAACP members are gathering
for their annual convention to debate, renew acquaintances and
regain momentum.
   The nation's oldest and largest civil rights group opens its
annual convention in Detroit on Sunday.
   ``It's the people from the various communities around the country
who set the positions. That's the beauty of this organization,''
said the Rev. Richard Dockery of Dallas, southwest regional director
of the NAACP.
   Annual dues were 50 cents when Dockery, 65, joined the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People in 1939. He lived
in Mobile, Ala., ``deep in the heart of Dixie, where you had to have
courage, or a shotgun.''
   In the years since, dues have grown to $10 a year. But now as
then, Dockery said, the NAACP is the most important voice for black
Americans.
   ``It's the organization for our people,'' he said before leaving
for Detroit last week.
   The NAACP, which claims 500,000 members nationwide, was founded
in 1909 by W.E.B. DuBois and others.
   Over the years, it has won many battles, including desegregation
of the military, schools and public facilities, voting and other
civil rights. Some, including the effort to overcome economic
inequality between the races, it has not. Other fights that appeared
won now are in doubt, said Benjamin Hooks, NAACP executive director
since 1977.
   A series of recent U.S. Supreme Court decisions ``just emasculate
the civil rights laws,'' Hooks said. ``In fact, it's going to get a
lot worse before it gets better.''
   ``It's a sad fact that we're still about the same thing we were
when we were founded in 1909 _ eliminating all forms of racial
discrimination. Racism, sexism are alive and well.''
   Despite the grim appraisal, the spirits of Hooks and other
delegates appeared joyful on the eve of the 80th annual convention.
He said the Supreme Court decisions have boosted interest in the
organization, particularly among young black professionals.
   For many members, the gathering offers a chance to see old
friends, share experiences and regain a spirit of hope, said Lulann
Sapp McGriff, San Francisco chapter president.
   McGriff, a member for 13 years and former national staff member,
said she looked forward to seeing the 1,300 young people
participating in the NAACP's annual ``black Olympics'' competition
in science, humanities and the arts.
   The ACT-SO competition, short for Afro-Academic, Cultural,
Technological and Scientific Olympics, will award $150,000 in
scholarships.
   ``For me, that is the highlight of the convention, seeing the
black young people showing their scholarship,'' McGriff said.
``You've got poets, writers, musicians _ it's a phenomenal thing to
see.''
   In addition to debating resolutions on topics ranging from AIDS
to urban decay, the delegates will get a chance to hear from a
parade of politicians, as well as an assortment of entertainers.
   Vice President Dan Quayle speaks Wednesday and 1988 Democratic
presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson on Thursday. Also appearing are
two members of President Bush's Cabinet _ Housing and Urban
Development Secretary Jack Kemp and Health and Human Services
Secretary Louis Sullivan.
   Other speakers include United Auto Workers union President Owen
Bieber, national Democratic Chairman Ron Brown, Michigan Gov. James
Blanchard and Detroit Mayor Coleman Young, one of the nation's most
powerful black leaders after 15 years at the helm of the nation's
sixth-largest city.
   Film maker Spike Lee, whose movie ``Do the Right Thing'' has
sparked a debate over race relations, and television talk show host
Oprah Winfrey also will appear.
   The displays of youthful talent and celebrity appearances, along
with the chance to swap stories with old friends, help lift the
spirits of NAACP activists engaged in the long, lonely battle for
racial justice, Hooks said.
   ``It gives them the renewed vigor to continue the fight,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
