<FIRST>r i AM-NorthKorea     07-08 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Korea,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Youth Festival Ends With Crowd Of 150,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150,000 spectators attended Saturday's closing
ceremony of a weeklong international youth festival in the North
Korean capital of Pyongyang, the communist government's official
news agency reported.
   North Korean President Kim Il Sung was among those attending the
ceremony, which was ``enveloped in a festive mood,'' said the report
monitored in Tokyo.
   The 13th World Festival of Youth and Students was the largest
international gathering staged by the government.
   Spectators from 180 countries filled the 150,000 seats of the new
May Day Stadium, where many of the festival's events were held, the
Korean Central News Agency report said.
   It described the event as ``a complete success'' that ``marked a
brilliant chapter in the history of the youth movement of the
world.''
   The festival, which began July 1, brought people from mostly
socialist nations together for athletic shows, photography and art
exhibitions, songfests, plays and discussions on various
``anti-imperialist'' themes.
   However, police earlier during the festival seized Danish and
Finnish human rights banners, and some European delegates accused
North Korea of using the gathering for self-promotion.
   The Danish banner called for human rights in North Korea, while
Finland's banner protested the Pyongyang government's refusal to
allow the rights group Amnesty International to attend.
   The Finn delegation reversed its decision to drop out of the
festival after North Korea apologized and said two Amnesty
International representatives would be given visas to attend.
Anmesty has cited rights violations in North Korea.
   The festival, the 13th since 1947, was last held in 1985 in
Moscow.
</TEXT>
