<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 1443EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-X-RatedHarvard     07-08 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-X-Rated Harvard,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harvard Tradition Includes Restricted Library Collection of Books
About Sex</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A picture book of Catherine the Great's
lewd furniture, a Cold War expose on communist sexual practices and
pristine copies of Playboy can be found among the 10.2 million tomes
at Harvard University.
   But to see them, you need to find the man who holds the key to
the XR collection.
   Down a steep stairway at Harvard's Widener library and behind a
heavy copper door that stays locked is the collection that makes
Edward Doctoroff, the man with the key, practically blush.
   But if he's red in the face, it's not because of the erotic
contents of the XR books and magazines, but because the whole idea
the locked collection is so old-fashioned, and because the
collection stopped growing years ago.
   ``It's a dead collection,'' said the succinct Doctoroff, head of
circulation services at Widener, the chief repository of the written
word at Harvard.
   ``XR'' does not stand for ``X-rated.'' The ``X'' means the books
are one of 20 categories of unusual books _ miniature books are
another such category _ and the ``R'' stands for restricted.
   Marion Schoon, chief of the library's reference collection,
believes as Doctoroff does that it's just an oddity of history that
the assortment of 1,000 books that analyze, philosophize, wax poetic
about and poke fun at sex are still housed separately, under lock
and key.
   ``This is sort of a remnant,'' she said.
   The XR collection was only actively assembled and added to for
less than 30 years. But the prudishness that was still the norm
three decades ago had nothing to do with its separate status _
librarians were concerned about the books getting lost.
   ``It was before my time, but apparently in the '50s, early '60s,
there was a sociology professor who found a lot of the books for his
course were not available,'' said Ms. Schoon. The books on the
reading list that concerned sex were missing from Widener's shelves,
so a restricted collection was created.
   ``Playboy had to be in there,'' she added, ``because they tended
to lose the centerfold.''
   But librarians quit labeling books XR sometime in the '70s, she
said. There was simply no need. Copies of the same books are now
found in the general stacks but no one bothers to steal them or cut
out their favorite pictures. Just over the road in Harvard Square
newsstands sell plenty of magazines to satisfy the salacious scholar.
   And Playboy is on microfiche.
   Not much traffic goes on in the XR nowadays; a week can go by
with fewer than five volumes checked out.
   So why continue to lock up ``Sexual Behavior in the Communist
World: An Eyewitness Report of Life and Love and the Human Condition
Behind the Iron Curtain'' with ``5,000 Adult Sex Words &amp; Phrases,''
and ``The Passions and Lechery of Catherine the Great''? Not to
mention better known literary ventures in sex by D.H. Lawrence,
``Lady Chatterley's Lover''; Henry Miller, ``Tropic of Cancer''; and
William S. Burroughs, ``Naked Lunch''?
   It's just lack of money, Ms. Schoon said. The XR collection would
vanish if there were resources to do all the work needed to disperse
the books throughout Harvard's vast library and change all the
records, Ms. Schoon said.
   ``It's sort of like a spiderweb, cataloguing. Pulling all the
cards. It's very labor intensive,'' Ms. Schoon said.
   The library is plenty busy adding 50,000 to 60,000 new volumes
every year. Reorganizing things for 1,000 books could slow things
down, Ms. Schoon said.
   So the XR collection stays as it is, a quaint memento of a time
when sex needed to be kept under lock and key.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
