<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     07-08 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burmese Opposition Leader Will Continue Campaign of Speeches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's main opposition leader, Aung San
Suu Kyi, said Saturday that despite ``veiled threats'' by the
military government, she will continue her speeches that have drawn
large crowds in Rangoon recently.
   The charismatic Suu Kyi, 44-year-old daughter of assassinated
independence hero Aung San, has garnered widespread popular support
since emerging at the head of last year's thwarted uprising for
democracy. Her outspoken condemnations are unprecedented in a
country cowed by years of authoritarian repression.
   Suu Kyi said she planned to deliver more speeches in Rangoon on
Monday, in spite of the government's demand that the opposition
leader end what officials decribe as her ``confrontational''
approach.
   The main target in Suu Kyi's repeated denunciations of military
rule is strongman Ne Win, who held Burma in an iron grip for 26
years until officially retiring a year ago.
   Suu Kyi, general secretary of the National League for Democarcy,
charges Ne Win continues to manipulate the government of Gen. Saw
Maung from the wings.
   A spokeswoman for her party claimed up to 1,000 members of the
league have been arrested since the military took power last
September.
   Speaking from Rangoon in a telephone interview, Suu Kyi accused
Saw Maung of threatening opposition groups when he spoke at a rare
press conference Wednesday.
   ``Two things emerged during Saw Maung's speech,'' Suu Kyi said.
``The first is that he has shown that he does not believe in
dialogue and the second was a veiled threat of force.''
   ``This is exactly the way Ne Win has always reacted when faced
with any kind of opposition,'' Suu Kyi said. ``This is why we are
convinced that Ne Win is still pulling the strings from behind Saw
Maung.''
   Ne Win, now 78, is held responsible for ordering the killings of
protesters during protests for political change last year. Troops
under Saw Maung killed at least hundreds when assuming power Sept 18.
   At his press conference, Saw Maung insisted Ne Win took no part
in national politics, but said: ``We are all here today because of
him, he taught us like a parent.''
   The pace of political dissent has quickened in Burma in the past
few weeks as large crowds have massed in Rangoon in defiance of a
10-month-old martial law order forbidding more than five people to
assemble.
   The government, however, has allowed the formation of political
parties and promised free elections next year.
   On Wednesday, more than 10,000 people rallied to hear Suu Kyi
speak in what diplomats said was the largest political gathering
since the army seized power. Diplomats said she addressed more large
crowds Thursday.
   On Saturday, residents said large crowds attended the funeral in
Rangoon of Mahn Win Maung, the last president of a
democratically-elected government in Burma. He died Monday at the
age of 73.
   Mahn Win Maung was elected president of Prime Minister U Nu's
government in 1957. The government was ousted by Ne Win's military
coup in 1962.
</TEXT>
