<FIRST>r a AM-JetEngines     07-08 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jet Engines,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Probe Of Apparent F-16 Engine Thefts Continues, But FBI Mum On Details</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILL AIR FORCE BASE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI remained tight-lipped
Saturday about its investigation of the apparent theft of three F-16
fighter jet engines from this northern Utah installation.
   The Salt Lake City FBI office would only confirm its terse Friday
announcement that the Pratt &amp; Whitney F100-PW-200 engines had been
recovered and were in government custody.
   A man who answered the phone at the FBI office Saturday would
identify himself only as ``Scott.'' He said he knew of no plans to
release further details during the weekend. ``We're not giving out
any information at all,'' he said.
   The $2 million engines _ each about 17 feet long, 3 feet in
diameter and weighing 3,200 pounds _ were discovered missing by Hill
maintenance personnel on Wednesday morning, said Hill spokesman
Louis Arana-Barradas.
   Neither the FBI nor Pentagon officials in Washington would
discuss a Friday night CBS News report that the incident may have
involved a government ``sting'' operation designed to crack down on
thefts of military property. CBS said a base employee offered to
sell the engines to undercover agents.
   The FBI refused to discuss the report, say where the engines were
found, or whether arrests had been made.
   ``I think maybe we'll be able to elaborate a little next week,
but right now things are just too sensitive,'' special agent Tim
Screen said Friday.
   Neither Screen nor other agents were available for comment
Saturday, the man answering the FBI telephone said.
   A prosecutor at the U.S. attorney's office, which likely would
file any charges resulting from the case, also declined to comment.
   ``We're not talking about it,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney
Stewart Walz.
   Arana-Barradas said base spokesmen were authorized to say only
that the engines had been found and ``were in government hands.''
   If the engines were stolen, he said, they would have had to leave
through one of three gates on the base that are manned 24 hours a
day by guards.
   Earlier, Hill spokeswoman Maj. Portia McCracken said
investigators believed the engines were taken off the base sometime
between noon July 1 and noon Monday.
</TEXT>
