<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 1634EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Angola-US     07-08 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola-US,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Savimbi's Future Apparent Sticking Point in U.S.-Angolan Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. talks with the Marxist government
Saturday on ending Angola's 14-year-old civil war appeared to stick
on the future of U.S.-backed rebel leader Jonas Savimbi.
   Herman Cohen, U.S. assistant secretary of state for African
affairs, said his meeting with President Jose Eduardo Dos Santos was
``very friendly and constructive.''
   ``I believe we'll be able to expand our dialogue in the future,''
said Cohen, on his first tour of southern Africa for the Bush
administration.
   Washington is calling for direct talks between Savimbi and
Angola's government in return for diplomatic recognition withheld
since the country's independence from Portugal in 1975.
   ``We have always supported normalization of relations with the
United States,'' Dos Santos said. ``And if it were possible to sign
some kind of accord today, we'd be prepared to do so. But we
understand the United States is not yet ready.''
   The United States has been furnishing Savimbi's rebel National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, UNITA, with $15 million
a year in military aid.
   Angola is insisting that Savimbi agree to a temporary withdrawal
or self-exile from the country while peace is worked out and UNITA
members are incorporated into civilian life.
   Following a June 22 summit of African leaders in Gbadolite,
Zaire, where Dos Santos and Savimbi shook hands and agreed to a June
24 cease-fire, there were reports Savimbi accepted such conditions.
   But Dos Santos called an Angolan delegation home from peace talks
in Kinshasa, Zaire, last weekend on grounds UNITA violated the
cease-fire.
   Savimbi had previously agreed to sit out of Angolan politics for
two years before returning to participate in democratic elections,
and Zambian President Kenneth Kaunda said after Gbadolite that
Savimbi had ``of his own decision'' agreed to go abroad temporarily.
   But in a news conference last week in the Ivory Coast and in a
subsequent interview with a Portuguese newspaper, Savimbi denied he
had ever made such a concession.
   Dos Santos said Saturday he told Cohen that Kaunda's statement
``constitutes the key element for the solution of Angola's internal
problems.''
   Cohen was also in Luanda to attend the fourth meeting of the
tripartite commission monitoring the U.S.-brokered Dec. 22 agreement
between Angola, Cuba and South Africa that is scheduled to lead to
independence for Namibia and set the stage for an end to Angola's
civil war.
   Both the United States and the Soviet Union, Angola's main
financial backer, are observers in the process that includes the
phased withdrawal of some 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola by
mid-1991. South Africa agreed to cease aid to UNITA in return for
the Cuban withdrawal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
