<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 1652EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Fish-CancerRisk     07-08 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fish-Cancer Risk,0809</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lake Michigan Fish Risk Canary or Red Herring?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD EGGLESTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canary or red herring? That's the debate
over a new study by the National Wildlife Federation claiming a
greater cancer risk than previously thought in Lake Michigan fish.
   The federation wants the hazards of toxic chemicals in the lake's
fish to serve much the same role as the canary in a coal mine,
measuring the region's environmental health.
   But critics say the federation's report issued late last month
amounted to a red herring that needlessly alarmed the public.
   Using a U.S. Environmental Protection Agency formula and more
than 100 health studies, the wildlife federation published a 17-page
booklet titled ``Lake Michigan Sport Fish: Should You Eat Your
Catch?''
   The booklet estimated at 1 in 100,000 the lifetime cancer risk of
eating 15 meals of coho salmon or walleyed pike tainted with
chemicals from the lake, to cite just one example.
   Experts are skeptical of such estimates.
   Risk estimates based on tests involving laboratory animals are
``purely guesswork,'' said Dr. Henry Pitot, director of the McArdle
Cancer Research Laboratory at the University of Wisconsin-Madison.
   They are ``make-believe numbers,'' said Dr. Sidney Shindell,
chairman of the department of preventive medicine at the Medical
College of Wisconsin in Milwaukee.
   ``It's all based on basically bad science,'' said biochemistry
professor Bruce Ames of the University of California at Berkeley.
   The amount of sun a person soaks up catching a Lake Michigan fish
probably poses a greater cancer risk than eating the fish, and
driving to the lake certainly is more life-threatening than eating
the fish, Ames said.
   Ames added that there is no comparison at all between the risk of
cancer in the environment and the risk posed by smoking, which is
responsible for about one-third of all cancer.
   Nevertheless, Wisconsin officials received telephone calls from
people as far away as Fargo, N.D., and Omaha, Neb., asking whether
they should throw away the Lake Michigan fish they caught on a
recent vacation, or cancel a planned trip.
   Angry commercial fishermen in Michigan called the wildlife
federation suggesting the group buy their unsold lake trout.
   Mark Van Putten of the federation's Great Lakes Natural Resources
Center in Ann Arbor, Mich., responded by suggesting the fishermen
market unsold fish to polluting industries.
   Sport fishing is an industry worth billions of dollars on the
Great Lakes, and charter boat operators and sportsmen's clubs are
anxiously watching the situation.
   State officials in Illinois, Indiana, Michigan and Wisconsin are
telling worried citizens that they are comfortable with health
advice based on U.S. Food and Drug Administration standards for
commercial fish.
   The official advice says people should trim the fat and skin from
smaller fish caught in Lake Michigan; that women and children should
not eat medium-sized fish; and that no one should eat very large
fish from the lake.
   The longer and older a fish, the more likely it is to have in its
tissues toxic chemicals like PCBs and the pesticides DDT, dieldrin
and chordane. The extra precaution on medium-size fish is directed
at women because of the danger PCBs pose to the reproductive system,
children because their relatively small body weight can magnify the
effect of eating a toxic substance.
   The official advisory does not attempt to rate cancer risk,
precisely because of the public confusion that creates, Lee
Liebenstein, toxic chemicals specialist for the Wisconsin Department
of Natural Resources, said.
   Van Putten, who was in charge of the two-year National Wildlife
Federation project, said the cancer-risk studies his group used are
the best science available, and are accepted by the EPA and other
government agencies.
   The federation's pamphlet recognizes that the risks are
estimates, but it provides citizens with valuable information they
need to set pollution cleanup priorities and demand action, Van
Putten said.
   ``Don't get frustrated, get mad and get active,'' he advises.
   ``Some of these risks are small compared with other risks in
society, but they're risks that ought to be reduced,'' said Jan
Beyea, a senior scientist with the National Audubon Society in New
York City.
   And even critics of risk estimates based on tests using
laboratory animals say people should not go hog wild about fish
bearing traces of chemicals.
   ``Before you eat a fish out of Lake Michigan for dinner every
evening, you should think about it,'' Ames said.
   Van Putten said fish caught in such places as Santa Monica Bay,
Calif.;, Quincy Bay, Mass.; the Ohio River; the Hudson River and
Puget Sound also are contaminated with traces of industrial and
agricultural chemicals.
   But more information is available about Lake Michigan fish than
about fish from other pollution hotspots, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
