<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-08 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Much Of The Nation Sizzles; 5th Day in 100s in Denver</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures were above normal Saturday across large parts of the
nation, with record highs in the western and northern Plains and
central Rockies, and strong thunderstorms developed over the Midwest.
   A stagnant upper-level high pressure system dominated the
nation's weather by spreading temperatures in the 90s from the
southern Atlantic Coast across the middle and lower Mississippi
Valley, much of the Plains and the central Rockies to interior
California.
   Rapid City, S.D., reached 103 degrees before 11 a.m., then rose
to a record 107.
   Other records included 97 at Cheyenne, Wyo.; 100 at Denver; and
101 at Williston, N.D. Casper, Wyo., tied its record of 100 and
Scottsbluff, Neb., tied its record of 105.
   The reading at Denver extended the city's consecutive days of 100
degrees or higher to five. During 118 years of weather
record-keeping at Denver, there had never before been more than two
consecutive days of triple-digit temperatures.
   Strong thunderstorms developed in unstable air near a warm front
over central Illinois and Indiana during the afternoon.
   Warm, very humid air from the Gulf of Mexico triggered showers
and thunderstorms from central Texas across the Gulf Coast states to
the Georgia and South Carolina coast.
   An upper air disturbance off the northern Pacific Coast produced
showers along the Washington coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57 at
Quillayute, Wash., to 111 at Needles, Calif. Saturday's low in the
Lower 48 states was 40 at Truckee, Calif., and Redmond, Ore.
   For Sunday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the lower Mississippi Valley along the eastern Gulf Coast
region into the Florida Peninsula, and from the eastern half of the
upper Great Lakes into the upper Ohio Valley and the lower Great
Lakes.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted in northern Maine; in the 70s and
80s along much of the Pacific Coast; in the 80s in the northern
Intermountain region between the Rockies and the Cascade Range, much
of Montana, and from northern Minnesota across the lower Great Lakes
into the northern Atlantic Coast states; above 100 across sections
of the central Plains and the middle Mississippi Valley, the central
Rockies, and from the Big Bend of the Rio Grande in Texas across the
desert Southwest into interior valleys of central and southern
California; and in the 90s in much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
