<FIRST>r a AM-PreachingHygienist     07-08 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Preaching Hygienist,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Preaching Hygienist Isn't Entitled To Unemployment Benefits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dental hygienist and born-again Christian
who was fired for preaching to patients can't expect to receive
unemployment benefits, the Michigan Court of Appeals ruled.
   Dr. J.B. Mulder Jr. fired Sharlyn Vanderlaan of Grand Rapids in
1986 after she ignored at least a dozen warnings to stop preaching
while she worked.
   A three-judge appeals court panel on Friday upheld rulings by the
Michigan Employment Security Commission and lower courts denying
Vanderlaan unemployment compensation.
   ``A dentist has the right to expect his dental hygienist, whose
work is often painful and requires the patient to be verbally and
physically submissive, to behave in a manner which does not add more
discomfort,'' the court said in rejecting Vanderlaan's claim that
she was exercising her First Amendment-protected right to free
speech.
   At least six of Mulder's patients changed dentists because of
Vanderlaan's preaching, according to court records.
   Vanderlaan's attorney, Keith Beauchemin, said she ``was compelled
by her faith to share it with just about anybody she had the
opportunity to ... even if it meant losing her job.''
   Vanderlaan found a part-time job with a dentist who lets her
preach. She currently is out of the country on a religious mission.
</TEXT>
