<DOCNO> AP890708-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 1754EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChickenShow     07-08 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicken Show,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>People Flock to Wayne for National Cluck-Off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WAYNE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Wayne Chicken Show, where bare-chested
male ``Chick `N' Dale'' dancers marched in a parade Saturday before
the National Cluck-Off competition, was something to crow about.
   ``I don't know if it's an honor to be a dumb cluck or not,'' said
John Vavra, 39, a hard-boiled construction worker who won the
cackling contest for the third consecutive year.
   He reclaimed the title despite the efforts of Bill Patrick of
Vassar, Mich., whose co-workers at a foundry raised $400 to give him
a crack at the championship.
   ``My fine-feathered friends egged me on to come out here,'' said
Patrick, 37, who placed third in the adult rooster competition.
   He began crowing because he didn't want his daughter to believe
roosters said ``cock-a-doodle-doo,'' like the sound one of her toys
made.
   Joelle Patrick, 11, apparently learned the correct cackle. She
won first place in the rooster imitation contest for children under
13.
   The chicken show began as an arts festival nine years ago in
Wayne, a community of about 5,200 people, about 120 miles northwest
of Omaha.
   ``We were trying to come up with a theme to show that art can be
found in anything'' said Jane O'Leary, one of the organizers.
``Someone said `chicken' and we laughed so hard.''
   There is no one chairman of the show, she said. ``We have no
pecking order.''
   The festival has grown into an event that attracts hundreds of
people. The Milton Waldbaum Co., an egg producer in nearby
Wakefield, has been one of many business supporters for the show. On
Saturday, festival workers dished out 2,000 omelettes during a free
feed in the morning, Ms. O'Leary said.
   Later, hundreds of people lined the streets to watch the Chicken
Show parade, where about half a dozen legislative aides in paper
chicken feet clucked as the ``Legislative Mutant Ninja Chickens.''
   ``It's the outreach program of the Capitol,'' Doug Clark, an aide
for Sen. Brad Ashford of Omaha, said with a laugh.
   They followed a bare-chested band of ``Chick `N' Dale'' male
dancers wearing brown paper bags and orange beaks on the their heads.
   The show also featured contests for egg dropping and having the
most beautiful beak. But the highlight was the annual hen and
rooster cluckng contest.
   Vavra came from Crete to cackle. ``As the chicken flies, it's 125
miles away,'' he explained. ``It's within squawking distance.''
   Besides Patrick, Vavra out-clucked John Agler, 34, of Wayne, who
had strutted to the championship from 1982-86.
   Agler, second in the adult rooster contest, began crowing as a
child growing up on a farm. A clucking judge in 1987, Agler decided
it's important to act as well as sound like a chicken.
   He began his performance by spreading a bag of corn on the stage.
Other contestants squatted, flapped wings and jerked their beaks.
   ``Basically, it's just fun,'' Agler said.
</TEXT>
