<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 1854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina 1stLd-Writethru a0538 07-08 0938</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0538,0962</SECOND>
<HEAD>New President Calls for Unity to Rebuild `Broken' Nation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with quotes, price increases expected;
CORRECTS that first transition from one freely elected president to another
in 61 years sted first in nation's history; pickup 13th pvs, ``Menem said...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlos Menem was sworn in Saturday
as Argentina's 46th president and asked his countrymen to help
rebuild a nation broken by inflation and divided by political
dissent.
   ``All of us together will cure Argentina or Argentina will die,''
said the 59-year-old son of Syrian immigrants in a sober,
conciliatory acceptance speech broadcast nationwide from Congress.
``This is the cruel choice.''
   Later, outgoing President Raul Alfonsin draped the blue-and-white
silk sash of office over Menem's shoulders, completing this
turbulent country's first transition from one freely elected
president to another in 61 years.
   ``I'm happy,'' Alfonsin told reporters before flying to his
hometown, Chascomus, 75 miles south of the capital.``I leave the
presidency without having known hatred or rancor. I leave the
presidency without having met a single enemy.''
   Menem, of the Peronist Party, takes over a country ravaged by
inflation and the worst recession in its 173-year history.
Alfonsin's inability to stabilize the economy forced him to resign
five months before his term officially ended.
   As real wages fell by more than 40 percent and unemployment
climbed to 10 percent this year, food riots broke out in several
cities. Looting and mass arrests occurred again last week in
Rosario, the third-largest city.
   By Menem's estimate, nearly a third of Argentina's 31 million
citizens live in poverty or suffer from illiteracy, malnutrition or
untreated sickness.
   After swearing in his eight-man Cabinet, Menem spoke from the
balcony from which former populist Juan Domingo Peron addressed
similar crowds during his ill-fated presidencies from 1946-55, and
1973-74.
   ``Argentina is passing through the worst crisis in its history,''
the slightly built president said. ``Enough of this situation. Tough
days are coming, but ... within a prudent period, we will harvest
good fruit.''
   Earlier, in his acceptance speech, the three-time provincial
governor and former political prisoner focused on the need for his
government to remedy the country's ills.
   ``Atop these ruins, all of us will build the home we deserve,''
he said in the 52-minute speech that was interrupted 32 times by
applause. ``From this broken country, we will raise a new fatherland
for ourselves and for our children.''
   Conquering inflation that in June soared by 114.5 percent will be
his ``first and fundamental battle,'' Menem said.
   He also pledged to resolve the military issue that sparked three
barracks revolts against Alfonsin: the trials of officers charged
with human rights abuses committed during the 1976-83 military
dictatorship.
   He received perhaps the most sustained applause when he pledged
to continue efforts to recover the Falkland Islands in the South
Atlantic over which Argentina and Britain went to war in 1982.
Argentina, which calls the islands the Malvinas, disputes Britain's
claim of ownership.
   Menem did not specify what anti-inflation policies he would
implement. Aides indicated last week his plan would be based on
price controls, a major devaluation of the austral, strict monetary
control and increased rates for public utilities and services.
   Economy Minister Miguel Roig was expected to announce price
guidelines and significant gas, public transport and utility
increases on Sunday. The price of milk, bread and many other basic
foods rose by 100 percent or more in the past two days.
   Menem said Argentina's $64 billion foreign debt, which includes
outstanding interest of about $4 billion, was ``imprudently
contracted over more than a decade'' but was an obligation the
country must repay.
   Menem hinted he might seek to call off the pending human rights
trials of 15 generals and three admirals rather than allow the
bitter, emotional proceedings to continue.
   ``We're not going to lose time in making concrete the
reconciliation of all Argentines,'' he said. ``The time has come for
each Argentine to extend his hand to his brother to make a chain
that is stronger than rancor, or discord, or resentment, or pain.''
   At least 8,960 alleged leftists were arrested, never seen again
and presumed executed during the military regime's crackdown on
subversion, according to a commission appointed by Alfonsin.
   Menem, at the time the governor of La Rioja Province, was jailed
for nearly five years following the overthrow of President Isabel
Peron in March 1976.
   Tens of thousands of well-wishers in this city of 8 million
cheered as Menem slowly made his way on the one-mile route from
Congress to Government House.
   ``Menem: the country needs you,'' said one banner. ``Long live
the fatherland,'' many shouted. A sign on a young boy dressed in a
jacket and tie stated, ``Thank you President Alfonsin, Thank you
President Menem for letting me grow up in democracy.''
   Menem's 1950s-era Cadillac convertible was flanked by police on
motorcycles and saber-carrying grenadiers on horseback.
   His victory in national elections May 14 marked the return of the
Peronist Party to the presidency for the first time since 1976, and
only the second time since 1955. Both previous Peronist presidencies
were overthrown by military coup.
   Nevertheless, there was little sense of jubilation like that on
Dec. 10, 1983, when Alfonsin formally replaced the discredited
dictatorship.
   Alfonsin and many Argentines thought the return of democracy
alone would spur economic growth. Argentines now hope Menem can
stave off disaster.
   ``Nobody expects Menem to make the country opulent,'' Peronist
Gov. Jose Octavio Bordon said in an interview. ``They just expect
that every day will be a little better.''
</TEXT>
