<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 1907EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-MexicanDebt     07-08 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexican Debt,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexican Government, Bankers Working on Debt Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mexican government and a 15-bank committee
were near agreement on a debt restructuring plan that would cut
Mexico's payments by almost one-fifth or $3 billion annually,
negotiators said Saturday.
   ``Mexico and the Bank Advisory Committee are close to agreement
in principle on a range of options, including debt and debt service
reduction as well as new money options,'' said a joint statement
from Jose Angel Gurria, Mexico's undersecretary for International
Financial Affairs, and committee co-chairman William R. Rhodes.
   ``The package under discussion should provide Mexico with
financial benefits in excess of $3 billion annually,'' the statement
said. No other details were provided, but both sides said talks will
resume Monday.
   A $3 billion cut in debt payments would mean a significant gain
for Mexico, which had expected to shell out about $16 billion this
year to foreign lenders.
   Mexico's foreign debt is second-largest in the developing world
after Brazil. The Mexican debt talks are seen as an important
indicator in the Third World debt crisis and as essential to
Mexico's economic recovery and stability.
   The negotiators issued the joint communique after talks that
lasted until nearly dawn, the Mexican government news agency Notimex
said. The talks, which began April 19, were held in New York City at
Citibank, the lead bank of the 15 on the Bank Advisory Committee for
Mexico.
   About $54 billion of Mexico's $107.4 billion foreign debt is owed
to private banks in the industrialized world.
   The New York Times reported Saturday that the Mexican government
was hoping for a 40 percent discount on a portion of that $54
billion, while the committee was considering 35 percent. Other loans
could be cut from the current 10 percent interest to 6.25 percent,
the Times said.
   Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari has made debt
reduction the centerpiece of his new administration's policies and
he has tried to woo lenders offering both economic and political
reform.
   The possibility of an agreement came at the 11th hour for Mexico,
which is not believed to have enough foreign reserves to cover
upcoming debt payments.
   Mexico's economy has been stifled by the debt crisis and other
economic setbacks such as high inflation. The average workers'
earning power has declined by 50 percent in six years and the
pressure on the Salinas government for debt relief is intense.
   Salinas has said his goal is to cut annual debt payments from 6
percent to 2 percent of the gross national product.
   In Washington, the Treasury Department issued a statement
praising the pending agreement.
   ``We welcome the additional progress which has been achieved by
the government of Mexico and the commercial banks toward finalizing
the terms of a financing package for Mexico involving debt
reduction, debt service reduction and new money,'' said the
statement.
</TEXT>
