<FIRST>u i AM-Romania-Hungary     07-08 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania-Hungary,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relations Between Romania And Hungary at Rock Bottom</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Warsaw Pact, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relations between Romania and Hungary
have hit ``a bottom point,'' a top Hungarian official said after
delegations from the two countries met Saturday.
   ``We took stock of all problems affecting our relations and the
only area where agreement was reached was that we are neighbors and
better relations are in (our mutual) interest,'' said Foreign
Minister Gyula Horn of Hungary.
   Horn's comments, carried by Hungary's state-run MTI news agency,
came after a meeting between Romanian Communist Party leader Nicolae
Ceausescu and Hungarian party chairman Rezsoe Nyers.
   Romania's official Agerpres news agency said the talks focused on
``several timely questions'' of bilateral cooperation.
   The brief report did not give details of the talks, but said the
two sides ``stressed the need ... to develop relations in a spirit
of good neighborliness (and) mutual interest.''
   ``The Hungarian delegation stated that relations are satisfactory
only in the economic field, while in the political sphere we have
reached a bottom point,'' MTI quoted Horn as saying.
   Bilateral relations between the Warsaw Pact nations are strained
over Bucharest's alleged discrimination against Romania's 1.7
million-strong Hungarian minority and the planned razing of
thousands of villages, including ethnic Hungarian communities.
   An estimated 30,000 Romanians, most of them ethnic Hungarians,
have fled to Hungary in the past two years.
