<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionPoll     07-08 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Poll,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Half of Americans Polled Expect New Abortion Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About half of Americans expect their states to
pass laws that would restrict abortions in light of the U.S. Supreme
Court's decision that such laws are constitutional, according to a
poll released Saturday.
   Fifty-two percent said they believed their states would pass new
laws, according to the poll in the July 19 issue of Newsweek.
   The Supreme Court on Monday upheld a Missouri law restricting
abortion, clearing the way for other states to do so.
   The court's decision met with disapproval by 53 percent of
Americans polled, while 37 percent approved.
   The poll also found that 75 percent of Americans believe any such
laws would lead to more teen-agers becoming mothers; 72 percent said
there would be more deaths due to illegal abortions; 69 percent said
they expect more limited access to abortions for poor women; and 63
percent said the laws would lead to more mistreated children.
   For the poll, The Gallup Organization interviewed 751 adults by
telephone July 6 and July 7. The margin of error is plus or minus 4
percentage points.
