<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Hostages     07-08 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Hostages,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother of Lebanon Hostage John McCarthy Dies of Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of British hostage John
McCarthy, held in Lebanon for more than three years, died of cancer
at a hospital in Cambridge Saturday, doctors said. She was 66.
   The precise nature of Sheila McCarthy's cancer was not disclosed
in a statement issued by her doctors. Her husband, Patrick, was at
her bedside when she died at Addenbrookes hospital, the statement
said.
   The couple's 32-year-old son John, a television journalist, was
riding in a taxi to Beirut's airport to catch a London flight when
he was kidnapped by gunmen on April 17, 1986.
   Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe said Mrs. McCarthy's was ``a
reminder to us all of the human tragedy of the kidnapping and the
sheer heartlessness of the kidnappers who ignored the family's
appeal to let Mrs. McCarthy see her son again before she died.''
   Mrs. McCarthy, in a statement issued June 21, appealed to her
son's abductors to set him free.
   It was relayed through her doctor, Terence Wheeler, who said at
the time: ``As Mrs. McCarthy's personal doctor, I appeal to those
holding John in the name of humanity, for which Islam is well known,
to show compassion and release John to his dying mother.''
   There was no response from the kidnappers. The statement followed
a similar appeal by Patrick McCarthy that was published in several
Beirut newspapers.
   In addition to McCarthy, 16 Westerners are still missing in
Lebanon. They include American journalist Terry Anderson, the
longest-held foreign captive. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   No group has claimed responsibility for McCarthy's abduction,
which came amid a wave of kidnappings of foreigners by pro-Iranian
Shiite Moslem zealots.
   McCarthy, employed by the London-based Worldwide Television News,
was seized two days after U.S. warplanes bombed Libyan targets in
retaliation for terrorist acts the United States alleged were
sponsored by Libya.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government allowed U.S.
warplanes to fly from bases in Britain for the attacks. The raids
caused widespread anger against the United States and Britain in
Moslem countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
