<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--UnderwaterListening     07-08 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Underwater Listening,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 300 Take The Plunge Into Underwater Listening</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOOE KEY NATIONAL MARINE SANCTUARY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 375
snorkelers and scuba divers really ``got down'' Saturday, taking the
plunge for some finger-snapping, flipper-slapping tunes at the
Underwater Music Festival.
   For three hours, Florida Keys radio station WWUS blasted tunes by
such artists at Jimmy Buffett and The Beach Boys through six
underwater speakers.
   ``When music is broadcast underwater it seems to envelope you
from all directions,'' said Bill Becker, the station's news director
and coordinator of the event. ``Because sound travels five times
faster underwater than it does in the air, it generates an
unforgettable effect.''
   The underwater speakers were hung from boats stationed at
strategic points above the coral reef to create the best
surround-sound effect, Becker said.
   Also piped through to the listeners were announcements concerning
reef conditions and preservation techniques.
