<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 2047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CoalStrike     07-08 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miners Converge on Logan For Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT HARVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOGAN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking coal miners will win their labor
struggle against The Pittston Co. if they stand together, a United
Mine Workers official and U.S. Rep. Bob Wise told about 2,000 union
members at a rally Saturday.
   ``Our forefathers and their forefathers fought so we could have
our rights,'' District 17 President Bob Phalen Phalen told miners
and their supporters at the rally.
   ``We've got to fight to keep those rights. It's everybody's
fight. Always remember that. It's everybody's fight,'' he said.
   The rally at a high school football field began with a procession
by 20 striking Eastern Airlines pilots from Atlanta.
   ``We just decided to come and join our union brothers here in
their battle against the attitude that seems to be prevalent in
management today,'' said Ed Miskotten, an Eastern Airlines captain.
   Wise, D-W.Va., praised the UMW for its patience in dealing with
Pittston and urged Pittston Chairman Paul Douglas to become
personally involved in negotiations.
   ``This is about a fair contract,'' Wise said, ``a contract that's
fair to the miners, and yes, fair to the company. ... Come back to
the table, Douglas, because if this goes on much longer we risk
unraveling the progress in labor and management relations made in
the past 15 years.''
   The rally came one day after UMW President Richard Trumka
announced a union-sanctioned, three-day memorial period starting
Monday. It was the UMW's first official sanction for miners to
protest Pittston since wildcat strikes began in mid-June.
   All UMW members east of the Mississippi River were asked to stay
away from work Monday through Wednesday, except those at
Westmoreland Coal Co., which used its memorial days in April.
   More than 37,000 miners have been on wildcat walkouts in eight
states, protesting Pittston's refusal to sign a national contract
negotiated by the UMW and the Bituminous Coal Operators Association.
As many as 16,000 miners have been on wildcat strikes in West
Virginia.
   A convoy of 80 cars and trucks from Stone, Ky., arrived for the
rally, which coincides with the end of a two-week summer vacation
for many UMW miners.
   ``This rally is showing the solidarity and support of the union
and its unity,'' said Alan DeMurray of Stone, a striking Pittston
miner.
   ``Right now, I think Pittston's pushed us as far as it can push
us,'' said DeMurray, who works at Pittston's Eastern Coal Co.
subsidiary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
