<FIRST>r a AM-CanadianVessels 1stLd-Writethru a0567 07-08 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canadian Vessels, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0567,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skippers, Crews of Seized Boats Return to Canada ^Eds: SUBS 4th graf,
`Wilson, master ..., to CORRECT that he captains the Fonzie, sted Viscount.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KETCHIKAN, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The masters and crews of two Canadian
fishing boats seized on suspicion of illegal fishing were in Prince
Rupert, British Columbia, on Saturday, the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service said.
   Masters Bruce Devereux and Howard Wilson, and their crews, were
taken to a ferry that left here late Friday, Mike Harpold of the INS
said. Their fishing boats remained docked in Ketchikan.
   The Coast Guard on Wednesday seized the 50-foot Viscount and the
40-foot Fonzie after it said the vessels were observed fishing in
U.S. waters of Dixon Entrance, between Southeast Alaska and Canada's
Queen Charlotte Islands.
   Wilson, master of the Fonzie, said he has fished for 10 years in
the area where the boat was seized. ``I do not believe I was over
the line,'' said Wilson of Parksville, British Columbia.
   He said idling his boat was costly. ``We're losing about $3,000 a
day to sit here,'' Wilson said.
   Earlier, Devereux told Canadian Press he was roughed up by
members of the Coast Guard party that boarded his boat. Coast Guard
spokesman Ed Moreth said the Canadians filed no complaints about
their treatment.
   A federal court complaint alleging illegal fishing and seeking
forfeiture of the vessels, gear and fish on board was filed Friday
in Anchorage. Canada filed with the State Department a protest
seeking release of the vessels.
   The 4,000 pounds of salmon aboard each boat were sold to a
Ketchikan cannery, with the payment to be held in court until the
matter is resolved.
</TEXT>
