<FIRST>r a AM-CecilandAlex     07-08 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cecil and Alex,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ventriloquist and Sidekick Are Buried Together</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cecil Carpenter and Alex were inseparable
in life, and so they will be in death.
   Cecil, the ventriloquist, and Alex, the little guy made of wood,
were buried together in Goshen Cemetery on Wednesday. It seemed
fitting, the family said.
   ``I think there's only one way to go. Alex has to go with him,''
said Cecil's brother, Norman.
   Cecil and Alex, partners for 10 years, played their last show
June 30 at the annual convention of the National Ventriloquists'
Association Fort Mitchell, Ky. After the performance, Cecil, 54,
collapsed and died.
   The ventriloquist's daughter, Sheila, said she probably was the
only dissenter when the family first talked about burying Alex with
her father. She thought a museum would be the best place for Alex.
   ``Then I changed my mind,'' she said. ``I got to thinking that
without my dad, he's nothing.''
   Norman Carpenter said any time his brother talked about himself
he always talked about Alex, too. ``They were a pair, like Lewis and
Martin, Abbott and Costello.''
   Gary Carpenter, Cecil's youngest son, said Alex's name always was
included on family Christmas cards. ``I remember when we all went to
California in 1981. ... we had to take stuff out of the car to make
room for Alex,'' he added.
   Sheila said Alex was like a little brother to her. She said that
when her father's work as a plumber took him out of town he would
take Alex with him. She said he entertained on his lunch break and
went to nursing homes to entertain after work.
   ``We enjoyed him and he was always around when we were kids,''
Warren Carpenter, Cecil's oldest son, said of Alex. ``One thing
about Dad was that he loved to make people happy.''
   Carpenter drove with his wife, Mary, to Fort Mitchell on June 29,
the day after he was released from St. Vincent Hospital in
Indianapolis, where he had been a patient for three weeks with a
heart ailment.
   Mrs. Carpenter then returned home, planning to pick up her
husband when the convention ended. Carpenter earlier had confided to
his brother about his heart problems and said he didn't think he had
much time left to live.
   He was ``very serious and very direct,'' Norman Carpenter said.
   Carl Brandenburg, also a ventriloquist and brother of Norman's
wife, said he saw Cecil and Alex's last performance. He said Cecil
sat down four or five times during the show and slurred some of his
words. Cecil apologized to the audience, explaining that he didn't
feel well, Brandenburg said.
   ``He was making people smile even in his last hours,'' the Rev.
Mark Minear said at the funeral service. ``He was a dearly loved man
and he dearly loved people. He and Alex brought many smiles to many
people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
