<FIRST>r a AM-Employee-Shooting 3rd-Writethru a0581 07-08 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Employee-Shooting, 3rd-Writethru, a0581,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coca-Cola Plant Worker Kills Two And Is Killed Himself In Police
Shootout</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS grafs 6-7, `Police identified ..., to give victim's age
and CORRECT spelling to Parson sted Parsons; picks up 8th graf, `Wallace
was ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX7</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTELL, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police shot and killed a just-fired Coca-Cola
plant worker Saturday after the man killed two co-workers, seized
and released a hostage, and emerged after seven hours with guns
blazing.
   ``They had no choice but to return the fire,'' Cobb County Police
Chief Culver Johnson said.
   John Wallace, 45, shot two men, briefly held another employee
hostage and then blockaded himself in an office at the Coca-Cola
West Metro Sales Center, Johnson said.
   Wallace negotiated with police in this northern Atlanta suburb
for most of the night. Around 5 a.m. police fired tear gas into the
building and Wallace agreed to come out without his guns, Johnson
said. But Wallace emerged firing his two guns at police, who shot
him.
   Wallace was taken to Cobb General Hospital, where he later died,
according to nursing supervisor Linda Cole.
   Police identified the slain co-workers as Maurice McCluskey, 34,
of Decatur and Alvin C. Parson, 27, of Powder Springs.
   Johnson said it was not immediately clear why Wallace was fired
from his job as a route salesman. Cobb County police Sgt. Mike Hicks
said McCluskey apparently was the superior who handled Wallace's
termination, and Parson was a co-worker.
   Wallace was told to clean out his locker when he arrived for work
around 10 p.m. Instead, he left and returned with guns and began
firing at workers at the plant, Johnson said.
   Later, a caller telephoned WSB-TV in Atlanta and identified
himself as Wallace, telling reporters he had shot two men. Police
said officials at the station initially acted as negotiators by
telephone.
   David Kenney, an associate producer at WSB, said the caller said
he worked 23 years for the company and said he shot the plant
manager who fired him and his supervisor.
   At one point during the night, Wallace took another man hostage
for more than an hour after the shootings, then released him. The
hostage was not identified.
   Eddie Wallace said his uncle ``felt like he didn't have any
alternative'' after losing his job.
   ``He felt like he'd rather be dead than start all over again. All
of a sudden someone tells you you don't have a job, and he just
snapped,'' said Eddie Wallace.
</TEXT>
