<FIRST>r i AM-Greece     07-08 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Gives Coalition Vote of Confidence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Tzannis Tzannetakis'
conservative-communist coalition won a vote of confidence from
Parliament early Sunday and a mandate to investigate political
scandals.
   The coalition, comprised of the conservative New Democracy party
and the communist-dominated Coalition of the Left and Progress, has
pledged it will complete its work in three months and call general
elections in October.
   The government said its main task will be to investigate former
officials of the Panhellenic Socialist Movement accused of
involvement in banking, financial and agricultural scandals. The
Socialists came in a distant second to the conservatives in the June
18 election.
   The coalition government was formed because no party one an
absolute majority in parliament.
   Parliament began debate on the new government's policy on
Thursday and completed it at midnight Saturday with a confidence
vote of 174-124.
   Absent from the roll call balloting was former Socialist Premier
Andreas Papandreou, who is recuperating at home after spending two
weeks in a hospital with pneumonia and kidney problems. One member
of the Coalition of Left and Progress abstained.
   New Democracy proposed on Friday that six Socialists, including
Papandreou, be investigated for alleged involvement in major
scandals during their eight years in office. All have denied any
wrongdoing.
   One scandal involves the embezzlement of $200 million from the
Bank of Crete.
   Papandreou issued a statement that said the coalition
government's plans were a ``new attempt to politically execute me.''
   He also accused it of ``violating elementary political and human
rights by shamelessly trying, without any evidence, to adopt the
months-long lies of the concerted mud slurring and libelous reports,
under the mantle of Parliament.''
</TEXT>
