<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 2150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AnselAdams     07-08 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ansel Adams,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stickers Settle Ansel Adams Photos Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge ordered a publishing company
to put stickers on its 1990 calendars to warn consumers that the
pictures were ``printed from copies of Ansel Adams photographs.''
   ``You can't pass off reconstituted photos as original and
mislead, knowingly or unwittingly, the purchasing public,'' U.S.
District Judge William D. Keller told Day Dream Publishing Inc.'s
lawyers Friday.
   Attorneys for Adams' estate and publisher filed suit against Day
Dream after the Santa Barbara publisher announced plans to publish a
book of Adams' photos obtained from the National Archives.
   The book and 1990 calendars by Day Dream bear the title, ``The
Mural Project,'' and include photographs the late Adams took for the
U.S. Interior Department to make mural-size prints to decorate
department buildings.
   Day Dream produced the book and calendars by re-photographing
images Adams had printed for the government in 1941-1942. Day Dream
lawyers argued that the images existed in the public domain.
   While prints of ``The Mural Project'' are easily available from
the government, Adams kept the negatives.
   Keller's ruling did not affect distribution and promotion of the
book because the attorneys agreed that all copies were sold or
already on store shelves. About half of the 122,000 calendars
printed also were already distributed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
