<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 2217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LutheranSynod     07-08 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lutheran Synod,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Luthern Church-Missouri Synod Re-elects President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Ralph A. Bohlmann was elected to his
fourth term as president of the Lutheran Church-Missouri Synod on
Saturday during the group's triennial convention.
   Bohlmann, 57, of St. Louis, was elected on the first ballot with
a 52.4 percent majority, or 589 votes. The closest contender was Dr.
Robert C. Sauer of St. Charles, Mo., who received 38.52 percent, or
433 votes. Sauer is a former vice president of the synod.
   Bohlmann was president of Concordia Seminary in St. Louis before
he was elected to head the synod in 1981 when he was part of a
conservative movement.
   Some conservatives in the church, who contend Bohlmann has become
too moderate, led an effort to unseat the president at the 1986
convention but narrowly failed.
   Other nominees for president were Dr. Eugene W. Bunkowske, a
professor at Concordia Theological Seminary, Fort Wayne, Ind.; Dr.
George F. Wollenburg, synod second vice president, Billings, Mont.;
and Dr. Robert D. Preus, president of the Fort Wayne seminary.
   The Lutheran Church-Missouri synod has its headquarters in St.
Louis and is the second-largest Lutheran church body in the United
States with 2.6 million members and more than 6,000 congregations.
</TEXT>
