<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Flight103     07-08 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Flight 103,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: U.S. Officials Know Names Of Flight 103 Terrorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. intelligence officials have identified four
terrorists allegedly responsible for planting the bomb that
destroyed Pan Am Flight 103 last December, a London newspaper
reported Sunday.
   The weekly Sunday Telegraph quoted unidentified officials as
saying the key figure in the attack was Hafez Kassem el-Dalkamuni, a
43-year-old Palestinian from the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command.
   The paper said he is in prison in West Germany awaiting trial for
possession of explosives.
   All 259 people aboard flight 103 and 11 people on the ground were
killed when the plane exploded over Lockerbie, in Scotland on Dec.
21. The new York-bound flight originated in Frankfurt, West Germany,
with a stopover at London's Heathrow airport.
   The newspaper said 21-year-old Khalid Jaafar of Lebanon, a second
suspected member of the Popular Front, is dead. He apparently was on
Flight 103 when it exploded, the newspaper said.
   The paper said that at first Jaafar was thought to be an
unwitting courier of the bomb. But ``intelligence officials have now
discovered a link between Jaafar and the PFLP-GC and suspect that he
was knowingly involved in the operation.''
   The paper said two other suspects, both members of the Popular
Front, were held briefly by West German police on explosives
charges, then released for lack of evidence before the bombing.
   ``They are now believed to be in a Scandinavian country, which
has been alerted by the United States,'' the paper said.``American
officials hope for an early arrest and will then seek their
extradition.''
   The paper did not identify the Scandinavian country and gave no
further details about the case.
</TEXT>
