<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Tour 1stLd-Writethru a0593 07-08 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Tour, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0593,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans Visit Soviet Military Installations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to ADD that Soviet Union to close five nuclear
reactors, quotes; No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 10 Americans Saturday toured a military
laser research center previously considered central to the Soviet
version of the U.S. anti-missile Star Wars program, according to
reports published Sunday.
   The Americans, including two physicists, three members of
Congress and two journalists, were the first foreigners allowed
inside the Shary-Shagan complex, located in Soviet Central Asia,
according to the New York Times.
   The Associated Press was not invited to participate.
   The tour included a look at a military laser once described by
the Pentagon as an operable anti-satellite weapon. But the American
visitors concluded the laser is probably too weak to damage U.S.
satellites.
   ``It seems to me it pretty clearly is not a power laser and
doesn't represent any threat as a weapon,'' Rep. Jim Olin, D-Va.,
told the New York Times. Olin is a former electrical engineer for
General Electric Co.
   ``If they wanted to have an anti-satellite program, this research
_ locating and tracking objects in space _ is certainly
applicable,'' he said. ``But it sure doesn't look like a beam
weapon.''
   The tour of the complex was part of President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or openness. The Soviet president
has called for reduction in conventional and nuclear forces and
doing away with the NATO and Warsaw Pact military groups that divide
Europe.
   Sary-Shagan has been an object of U.S. interest since 1984, when
the Pentagon published information about the compound based on
satellite photographs and identified it as the heart of an
``ominous'' laser weapons research and development program, the
paper said.
   It formed the heart of an aggressive campaign to justify
President Reagan's Strategic Defense Initiative, known as Star Wars,
in 1985.
   ``It's incredible to think that the Pentagon S.D.I. folks
probably got an extra $10 billion because of this place,'' Frank Von
Hippel, a Princeton University physicist who was among those touring
the facility, told the New York Times.
   ``It looks like a tool that's been left out to dry for 25 years.
It's got 19 counter-top-sized ruby laser, a welding-sized laser,
1960s vintage computers and a couple of one-meter mirrors in an
air-conditioned building,'' Von Hippel told the Washington Post.
   On Friday, the visiting Americans were the first to enter the
Kyshtym nuclear complex in the Ural mountains where the Soviet Union
has produced plutonium for its nuclear weapons since 1948, according
to the New York Times.
   The Washington Post reported Sunday that the Soviet government
has decided to shut down all five nuclear reactors producing
plutonium for nuclear weapons at the top-secret military center.
   Gorbachev said three months ago that three reactors would be
closed out of an estimated 13 throughout the country.
</TEXT>
