<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Pipeline     07-08 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pipeline,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pipeline Regulations Called `Regulatory Black Hole'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vague laws have left underground
pipelines ``a regulatory black hole,'' a congressman said Friday as
hearings began in the gasoline pipeline explosion that killed two
people, injured 31 and destroyed 10 homes.
   ``It appears that the end result is the companies are regulating
themselves,'' said Rep. George E. Brown Jr. as the House Public
Works and Transportation Committee's investigative subcommittee
convened.
   The May 25 gasoline pipeline explosion devastated the San
Bernardino neighborhood of Muscoy 13 days after a runaway Southern
Pacific train derailed on a curve and slammed into the same
neighborhood.
   The train wreck was blamed for the damaging the 14-inch gasoline
line of Calnev Pipe Line Co. Residents had been assured the
neighborhood was safe, although they insisted before the explosion
that they could smell gasoline.
   So haphazard is pipeline regulation, the committee noted, that
the state fire marshal's office had no record of the Calnev line,
even though it supplies 90 percent of the gasoline to the city of
Las Vegas, Nev. and nearly all the jet fuel to George and Edwards
air force bases.
   ``This scenario has presented us with a regulatory black hole,''
said Rep. Glenn M. Anderson, chairman of the subcomittee.
   The hearing began with dozens of residents of the devastated
Muscoy neighborhood looking on. Testimony was expected from several
officials, including City Attorney James Penman, who fought in state
and federal court to stop the line from being restored along the
same course.
   Calnev agreed to numerous suggestions and complied with
guidelines set up by federal officials to restore the pipeline, but
insisted on restoring the pipeline along its original course through
the neighorhood.
   State and federal judges told the city they could do nothing to
change Calnev's plans.
</TEXT>
