<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Uno     07-08 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Uno,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Prostitution Group Writes Letters Criticizing Uno</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-prostitution group has criticized Prime
Minister Sousuke Uno for allegedly keeping paid mistresses in a
letter sent to women's groups in the industrialized countries
meeting next week in Paris, according to news reports Friday.
   Kyodo News Service said the Study Group for Prostitution Problems
sent letters Friday to 77 women's organizations in the United
States, Britain, France, West Germany, Italy and Canada.
   Japan is the seventh member of the group of industrialized
countries whose leaders will meet in Paris next week.
   ``We want you all to know what kind of person Prime Minister Uno
really is,'' Kyodo quoted the letter as saying. ``Even though the
prime minister has been accused of keeping paid mistresses,
including a geisha, he has kept being evasive without clearly
denying it.''
   Uno has denied doing anything immoral. He has refused to comment
further since the allegations first were made last month.
   The letter also said the group was demanding Uno's resignation,
Kyodo reported. The group was not available to confirm the report
Friday night.
