<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0613EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpill     07-08 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tests in Tanker Grounding Show No Drugs or Alcohol</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ The captain and mate of a Greek tanker that
ran aground on a reef off Newport, spilling 420,000 gallons of
heating oil, were not drinking or using drugs at the time, according
to test results released Friday.
   ``We have preliminary results that are negative,'' said Mike
Benson, a spokesman for the National Transportation Safety Board in
Washington, D.C. ``We're not going to comment beyond that.''
   Benson said the tests, performed at the University of Utah, would
be run a second time for confirmation. He did not know all the drugs
for which the blood was screened.
   The tests confirmed the observations of Gov. Edward D. DiPrete
and Coast Guard officers who boarded the World Prodigy after it
slammed into Brenton Reef June 23. They said Capt. Iakovos
Georgudis, 43, did not appear impaired.
   Georgudis admitted he simply made a mistake and navigated the
ship onto the reef at the mouth of Narragansett Bay, DiPrete said. A
helmsman told a Coast Guard-NTSB investigating panel he saw the red
warning buoy on the wrong side of the ship, but did not tell the
captain.
   The World Prodigy did not have a harbor pilot on board at the
time. Pilots are required for commercial ships to navigate the bay.
   The spill was cleaned up with little immediate environmental
damage, although scientists still are monitoring for long-term
damage to fish and lobster larvae and the small plants and animals
on which they feed. The Coast Guard estimated the cleanup cost
almost $2 million.
   Georgudis faces two misdemeanor charges of violating federal
pollution laws, but a grand jury is investigating to determine if
there was gross negligence, which could elevate the charges to
felonies.
   Because of a mixup at the time, usable blood samples were not
taken until 19 hours after the accident, but officials said they
still could be used for screening.
   A state grand jury investigating possible violations of state
pollution or pilotage laws met again Friday and heard testimony from
the Coast Guard and a lobsterman who saw the grounding, said Lee
Baker, an attorney general's spokeswoman.
   It is not expected to hear any more witnesses when it reconvenes
next week, she said.
   The World Prodigy arrived Monday at a New York City drydock for
repairs.
</TEXT>
