<DOCNO> AP890708-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-89 0114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0644 07-08 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fires Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0644,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scores of Brush and Range Fires Char Thousands of Acres in U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE total land consumed; ADDS details on
fires in Washington and Colorado. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An army of firefighters renewed its offensive Friday against four
wildfires that charred more than 16,000 acres in Utah, but weekend
forecasts for wind and lightning had some Western authorities
worried about the threat of new fires.
   ``We're just scared to death, to tell you the truth,'' said Ray
Tate of the Bureau of Land Management's Vernal, Utah, office.
   Forest and range fires have burned more than 25,000 acres of land
in Arizona, and 23 new fires began Thursday and Friday from
lightning strikes in New Mexico, bringing the total number of blazes
burning to at least 55.
   In south-central Alaska, the Swinging Dome Fire about 200 miles
west of Anchorage grew to 11,000 acres and was fought by three
16-person crews, with another seven crews expected, state foresters
said.
   Fires also charred land in California, Colorado, Georgia, Wyoming
and Washington.
   And though firefighters reported progress against some fires,
National Weather Service officials said they faced a weekend of
continued heat and storms that could reignite blazes and cause new
ones.
   In Utah, the Diamond Peak fire, 20 miles west of the Colorado
border and just north of Interstate 70, had consumed 9,500 acres.
Four fresh 20-member crews were fighting the blaze, bringing to 400
the number of people on the line.
   Three fires burned in Ashley National Forest, in northeastern
Utah. Containment of the nearly 1,400-acre Rough Canyon fire just
south of Duchesne was expected Saturday, and major assaults were
launched on the Uinta Canyon fire, which has consumed 3,600 acres,
and the Six Mile Creek fire, which has scorched 1,200 acres.
   In Wyoming, 500 firefighters battled a 2,400-acre fire in
Wyoming's Bridger-Teton National Forest. Fire containment lines had
been dug around 25 percent of the blaze, which began Tuesday.
Officials said containment wasn't expected before late next week.
   ``The potential is for very high fire danger by the weekend,''
said forest spokesman Ed Christian. ``It's going to be low humidity,
high temperatures and probably some moderate winds in there.
Hopefully they can hold what they've gained.''
   In Arizona, temperatures above 100 degrees, low humidity and
extended drought conditions were largely responsible for the
increased dryness, officials said.
   Coronado National Forest Supervisor Jim Abbott said the Marijilda
fire that consumed 2,200 acres, and the 3,000-acre Chiva fire in the
Rincon Mountains near Redington Pass east of Tucson, were being
given top priority.
   He said the Marijilda fire was being fought with 260
firefighters, five air tankers and four helicopters and was of
special concern because of fears it could spread upward from its
present 7,000-foot level to the habitat of an endangered red
squirrel.
   Officials said the 376,000 acres closed to public recreational
use will remain closed until dampened by rain.
   None of the fires was in populated areas. Gov. Rose Mofford took
an aerial tour of some of the fires on Friday and characterized the
situation as serious but not disastrous.
   A 7,700-acre fire along the Great Divide in southwestern New
Mexico that has been raging out of control since Monday should be
contained by next Monday, said U.S. Forest Service spokesman Jim
Payne.
   In Georgia, a 500-acre fire that broke out when lightning struck
in the Okefenokee Swamp in Fargo was 15 percent contained, said
Chris Zajicek, fire information officer for the U.S. Forest Service.
   In Washington, a range fire fanned by gusting winds spread over
1,000 acres south of Omak, and the Okanogan County Sheriff's
Department evacuated some people from their homes.
   The fire in north central Washington began Friday, and 20-25 mph
winds spread it rapidly, Department of Natural Resources spokesman
Bill Wilburn said.
   There were no injuries nor reports of structural damage, but some
county roads north of the blaze had been closed.
   In Hurlton, Calif., a brush fire whipped by hot winds burned out
of control, consumed nearly 200 acres and destroyed four homes.
Several structures were ordered evacuated, including a day care
center, authorities said.
   Karen Terrill, a spokeswoman for the state Forestry Department,
said six tankers, three helicopters, 35 engines and 10 hand crews
were on the scene about 65 miles north of Sacramento. Fifty
additional engines had been requested, she said.
</TEXT>
