<SECOND>AM-India-Chemical,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ship Carrying Mustard Gas Component Returns to Bombay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German ship loaded with a mustard gas
component produced in India has returned to Bombay from Dubai, where
the shipment was halted, a port official said Friday.
   The Seacrest Pioneer carrying thionyl chloride entered Indian
territorial waters on Thursday and was now anchored about 1{ miles
off the Bombay Port, dock manager George Mampilli said.
   He said the thionyl chloride would be unloaded Sunday or Monday.
   The chemical, used to make pesticides, was manufactured by the
Bombay-based Transpec company and a West German company, Rheineisen
Chemical Products, contracted to deliver more than 250 tons of it to
Iran.
   Rheineisen halted the shipment at Dubai when West German
prosecutors opened a criminal investigation of the transaction.
   Rheineisen official Mojtar Ashtari said last week the company had
no indication the shipment might be used to produce poison gas.
</TEXT>
