<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Tues., July 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soft Landing or Hard, There's A Price To Pay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only once before in the past half-century has the
economy made a truly soft landing when it was headed toward
recession. That was in 1967, and it was made possible by war.
   As the economy faded in that year, thanks as usual to tight
monetary policy by the Federal Reserve, the military buildup
provided enough thrust to keep things going. But the price was
steep, and it is still being paid.
   The price was budget deficits, and those deficits led in the
1970s to some of the worst inflation ever experienced by Americans _
month after month of double digit rates, accompanied by interest
rates that exceeded 20 percent.
   While cause-effect becomes tenuous at that point, you can argue
that the inflation and other evidence of disequilibrium in the 1970s
provoked the big recession of the early 1980s that sent unemployment
too into double digits.
   In retrospect, therefore, the wonderfully soft landing of 1967
may have done little more than spread the damage over a longer
period of time than might have been the case. Some benefit! Might a
crash have been better?
   The soft landing concept, nevertheless, is back in the news _ and
is, in fact, the subject of perhaps the most popular economic debate
of the year. The lines are drawn: Will it or will it not be a soft
landing?
   No military buildup can save the economy this time; in fact, the
trend is toward lowering military expenditures. Consumers,
two-thirds of the economy, aren't in a buying mood, and that mood
could grow gloomier if jobs are lost.
   But there is support out there, according to Roger Brinner and
David Wyss, DRI McGraw-Hill economists.
   High on their support list is the expectation that exports will
remain strong, partly because European and Japanese economies are in
a different stage of the business cycle. Their economies should
continue to grow as ours fades.
   They expect a healthy world economy will boost U.S. export
voluume 10.4 percent in 1989, less than the 18 percent growth of
1988 but still affording strong support for the gross national
product.
   In fact, they expect that exports will contribute 2.1 percentage
points to real GNP growth in 1988 and 1989, ``just the same boost
that military spending contributed in 1966 and 1967.''
   Business investment, continuing to show strength, is likely to
help buffer the landing. Brinner and Wyss believe this segment of
the economy might even be robust, based on optimistic plans and a
backlog of unfilled orders.
   Then there's housing. Much of the news in recent weeks has had a
negative tone, but that's because of a decline in housing
production. That's just one aspect of the picture. In contrast,
sales may pick up as mortgage rates fall.
   If they are correct, the economy could glide to a soft landing
instead of scraping and banging itself along the runway.
   But those soft landings may tend to be dragged out. Fewer people
may get hurt, but the pain may be prolonged. Less damage may be done
immediately, but perhaps more over the following months.
   On the other hand, it may be possible to survive a crash and
quickly get on with business so long as the fuselage isn't ruptured.
Quick and damaging might not be worse than long and painful.
   Clearly, the Federal Reserve has chosen to seek a soft landing,
but that doesn't mean it will get it. It doesn't have as precise an
instrument panel as it would like, and it could make some serious
errors.
   It will have to be even luckier or more skillful than in 1967,
say Brinner and Wyss. And who can forget the aftermath of that soft
landing?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Tues., July 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
