<FIRST>s f BC-WeeklyFarm Adv09   07-08 0837</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 09,0862</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 9, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>It's a Time of Year When Farmers Keep Fingers Crossed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This is a time of year when farming can be more
frustrating than usual, when the weather gods and market forces seem
to conspire for good or evil.
   Seeds have been planted, plans have been made or at least
tentatively drawn up. Now, if only the right combination of sun and
rain comes along. If only consumer appetites hold just right for
beef, or pork, or poultry.
   Except for winter wheat, which already has shown its
drought-tattered profile, the production of most other 1989 crops is
still to be determined.
   In just a month, however, when USDA issues its monthly crop
production report on Aug. 10, the pattern for corn, soybeans and
other major crops will be pretty well established.
   From then on, although there will be further revisions through
the fall months, farmers, private analysts, foreign buyers and USDA
economists will have a fairly accurate picture of U.S. agricultural
supply and demand for 1989-90.
   Meanwhile, there are and will be hundreds of forecasts,
projections, educated guesses, computerized profiles and assorted
dart-board analyses of how the U.S. agricultural economy is shaping
up for the year ahead.
   The USDA, in the words of economist Don Seaborg, says that
``cautious optimism marks the outlook'' for farmers and consumers.
   ``Unless the weather turns dry or becomes too wet over an
extended area of the country later on this summer, there will be
large harvests of food crops,'' Seaborg says. ``Along with plentiful
meat production, the outlook points to continued abundant supplies
of food.''
   A team of USDA economists _ Ken Nelson, Fred White, Kevin Bost,
Lee Christensen, Larry Witucki, Sara Short and Jim Miller _ said in
a report in the July issue of Agricultural Outlook magazine that
timely rains have improved crop prospects and that forage and feed
costs are falling.
   ``A surge in fed cattle supplies has weakened cattle prices,
which will remain under downward pressure through early summer,''
the report said. ``Hog producers' losses since last fall have sapped
their financial strength. So hog production decisions will depend
critically upon what happens to feed prices this summer.''
   A large number of cattle in the marketing pipeline caused the
slaughter market to decline since late March, prompting feedlots to
sell cattle earlier and at lighter weights, the report said. For
example, average slaughter weights declined by 10 pounds per head
for steers and 12 pounds for heifers from March to May.
   Dry weather, poor pasture conditions and low stocks of hay in
early spring forced more cattle into feedlots.
   Although market prices of slaughter cattle dropped less than $1
per 100 pounds in May to about $74.50 per hundredweight, analysts
said prices may average in the range of $69 to $72 through early
summer.
   ``Retail Choice (grade) beef prices reached record levels in May
but are expected to decline into summer, partly because of the
increased production and already lower cattle prices,'' the report
said.
   Hog farmers' plans also will depend greatly on what happens to
corn and soybean crops this summer.
   Breeding herds were scaled back last summer as rising feed costs
cut into hog producers' returns, although analysts said the cutback
was modest by historical standards when cost-price squeezes
developed.
   ``One factor that may have buffered herd liquidation is that hog
producers entered last year's drought in a relatively strong
financial position,'' the report said. ``Net returns both in 1986
and 1987 were the highest in recent history.''
   If normal crop conditions prevail and feed costs decline, net
returns to hog producers will improve. As that happens, inventories
of breeding hogs should stabilize by the end of the year.
   Some other observations:
   _Broiler producers continue to be encouraged by good prices. Net
returns averaged 9 cents per pound in the first quarter, compared
with 6 cents in the fourth quarter of 1988. Production is expected
to increase about 5 percent this year to another record level.
   _Turkey production is expected to increase about 3 percent this
year. Wholesale prices may average in the range of 70 to 73 cents
per pound, up about 17 percent from 1988.
   _Production of table eggs is expected to drop about 4 percent in
1989, reflecting cutbacks in the laying flock because of last year's
low profit margins. Net returns to producers were about 11 cents per
dozen in the first quarter and are expected to ``remain positive''
for the remainder of this year.
   _Demand for dairy products has shown unusual strength for this
time of year, with prices rising during the heavy supply period of
spring. Much of that was due to the demand for non-fat dry milk.
International prices of powdered milk is expected to remain strong
in the second half of 1989, meaning that domestic prices probably
will continue up. Cheese prices also can be expected to rise.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday July 9</NOTE>
